1
00:00:00,240 --> 00:00:04,800
Today, I'm speaking with Michael Nielsen. You have 
done many things. You're one of the pioneers of  

2
00:00:04,800 --> 00:00:08,320
quantum computing, wrote the main textbook 
in the field of the open science movement. 

3
00:00:08,320 --> 00:00:12,000
You wrote a book about deep learning 
that Chris Olah and Greg Brockman  

4
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:15,760
credit with getting them into the field.
More recently, you're a research fellow  

5
00:00:15,760 --> 00:00:20,320
at the Astera Institute and writing a book 
about religion, science, and technology. 

6
00:00:20,320 --> 00:00:25,120
I'm going to ask you about none of those things.
The conversation I want to have today is,  

7
00:00:25,120 --> 00:00:31,440
how do we recognize scientific progress?
It's especially relevant for AI because  

8
00:00:31,440 --> 00:00:35,120
people are trying to close the RL 
verification loop on scientific discovery. 

9
00:00:35,120 --> 00:00:39,920
What does it mean to close that loop?
But in preparing for this interview,  

10
00:00:39,920 --> 00:00:43,920
I've realized that it's a more 
mysterious and elusive force,  

11
00:00:43,920 --> 00:00:46,400
even in the history of human 
science, than I understood. 

12
00:00:46,400 --> 00:00:51,200
I think a good place to start will be 
Michelson-Morley and how special relativity  

13
00:00:51,200 --> 00:00:56,800
is discovered, if it's different from the 
story that you get off of YouTube videos. 

14
00:00:58,800 --> 00:01:01,440
I will prompt you that way, 
and then we'll go in there. 

15
00:01:02,560 --> 00:01:09,920
Michelson-Morley is the famous result often 
presented as this experiment that was done in  

16
00:01:09,920 --> 00:01:15,040
the 1880s that helped Einstein come up with the 
special theory of relativity a little bit later,  

17
00:01:15,760 --> 00:01:21,120
changing the way we think about space and time 
and our fundamental conception of those things. 

18
00:01:21,760 --> 00:01:27,600
And there's a big gap, I think, between the 
way Michelson and Morley and other people  

19
00:01:27,600 --> 00:01:32,000
at the time thought about the experiment and 
certainly the way in which Einstein thought  

20
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:39,280
or did not think about the experiment.
In actual fact, he stated later in his  

21
00:01:39,280 --> 00:01:42,880
life he wasn't even sure whether he 
was aware of the paper at the time. 

22
00:01:42,880 --> 00:01:46,880
There's a lot of evidence that he probably was 
aware of the paper at the time, but it actually  

23
00:01:46,880 --> 00:01:52,480
wasn't dispositive for his thinking at all.
Something else completely was going on. 

24
00:01:55,840 --> 00:02:01,200
What Michelson and Morley thought they 
were doing was testing different theories  

25
00:02:01,200 --> 00:02:05,280
of what was called the ether.
If you go back to the 1600s,  

26
00:02:05,280 --> 00:02:13,760
Robert Boyle introduced the idea of the ether.
We know that sound is vibrations in the air. 

27
00:02:14,480 --> 00:02:16,480
Boyle and other people got 
interested in the question of  

28
00:02:16,480 --> 00:02:21,120
whether light is vibrations in something, 
and they couldn't figure out what it was. 

29
00:02:21,120 --> 00:02:24,480
Boyle did an experiment where he 
tested whether you could propagate  

30
00:02:24,480 --> 00:02:28,960
light through a vacuum. He found that 
you could. You couldn't do it with sound. 

31
00:02:28,960 --> 00:02:32,400
He introduced this idea of the ether, 
and for the next two hundred or so years,  

32
00:02:32,400 --> 00:02:38,400
people had all these conversations about 
what the ether was and what its nature was. 

33
00:02:38,400 --> 00:02:44,640
The Michelson and Morley experiment was really an 
experiment to test different theories of the ether  

34
00:02:44,640 --> 00:02:50,240
against one another, in particular to find out 
whether or not there was a so-called ether wind. 

35
00:02:50,240 --> 00:02:55,760
The idea was that the Earth is maybe 
passing through this ether wind. 

36
00:02:55,760 --> 00:03:03,280
And if it is passing through the ether 
wind and you shoot a light beam parallel  

37
00:03:03,840 --> 00:03:07,440
to the direction the ether wind is going 
in, it'll get accelerated a little bit. 

38
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:12,800
If it's being passed back in the opposite 
direction, it'll get slowed down a little bit,  

39
00:03:12,800 --> 00:03:16,400
and you should be able to see this in 
the results of interference experiments. 

40
00:03:16,400 --> 00:03:22,720
What they found, much to their surprise, 
was that in fact there was no ether wind. 

41
00:03:22,720 --> 00:03:26,720
That ruled out some theories of the 
ether, but not all, and Michelson  

42
00:03:26,720 --> 00:03:32,480
certainly continued to believe in the ether.
This is what was a shocking part of reading  

43
00:03:32,480 --> 00:03:36,960
this story from the biography of Einstein that 
you recommended by... what was his first name? 

44
00:03:36,960 --> 00:03:38,480
Abraham Pais.
Abraham Pais.  

45
00:03:38,480 --> 00:03:45,280
Subtle is the Lord. Also from Imre Lakatos, The 
Methodology of Scientific Research Programmes. 

46
00:03:45,280 --> 00:03:51,200
The way it's told is that Michelson-Morley 
proved that the ether did not exist. 

47
00:03:51,200 --> 00:03:55,520
Therefore, it created a crisis in physics 
that Einstein solved with special relativity. 

48
00:03:56,560 --> 00:03:58,640
What you're pointing out is he 
actually was trying to distinguish  

49
00:03:58,640 --> 00:04:02,080
between many different theories of ether.
If you're in space or if you're on Earth,  

50
00:04:02,080 --> 00:04:06,320
it's the same direction of ether, or maybe the 
ether wind is being carried around by the Earth,  

51
00:04:06,320 --> 00:04:08,960
and so you can't really experience it on Earth.
But if you go to a high enough altitude,  

52
00:04:08,960 --> 00:04:12,400
you might be able to experience it.
In fact, Michelson's experiments,  

53
00:04:12,400 --> 00:04:17,360
the famous one is 1887, but he conducted 
these experiments for basically two decades. 

54
00:04:17,360 --> 00:04:19,360
For longer than that. He conducted 
the first one in 1881, I think,  

55
00:04:21,280 --> 00:04:26,720
but he continued to believe until he died.
He died, I think it was 1929 or so. It was the  

56
00:04:26,720 --> 00:04:34,560
late twenties. He was still doing experiments in 
the 1920s about whether or not the ether existed. 

57
00:04:34,560 --> 00:04:38,080
So he continued to believe in 
the ether to the end of his life. 

58
00:04:38,080 --> 00:04:42,000
I think the last public statement he 
made was a year or two before he died,  

59
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:48,080
and he basically still believed it at that point.
In fact, there was another physicist, Miller,  

60
00:04:48,080 --> 00:04:51,600
who kept doing these experiments in the 1920s.
He thought that if he went to a high enough  

61
00:04:51,600 --> 00:04:57,520
altitude, Mount Wilson in California… 
"Oh, I'm high enough that the ether  

62
00:04:57,520 --> 00:05:03,040
winds are not being dragged by the Earth.
And I've measured the effect of the ether." 

63
00:05:03,040 --> 00:05:06,160
Einstein hears about this and he says, and 
this is where you get the famous quote,  

64
00:05:06,160 --> 00:05:10,240
"Subtle is the Lord, but malicious He is not."
Anyways, I think the reason the story is  

65
00:05:10,240 --> 00:05:16,880
interesting is for many different reasons.
One of the ways in which the real history of  

66
00:05:16,880 --> 00:05:22,720
science is different from this idea you get of the 
scientific method is that you really can't apply  

67
00:05:22,720 --> 00:05:28,480
falsification as easily as you might think.
It's not clear what is being falsified. 

68
00:05:29,040 --> 00:05:32,080
Is it just another version of the theory 
of the ether that's being falsified? 

69
00:05:33,360 --> 00:05:36,960
Certainly you can't induce the theory 
of special relativity from the fact  

70
00:05:36,960 --> 00:05:41,040
that one version of the ether seems to 
be disconfirmed by these experiments. 

71
00:05:42,480 --> 00:05:47,600
It certainly doesn't show that ideas about 
falsification are wrong or falsified,  

72
00:05:47,600 --> 00:05:53,600
but it does show that the most naive ideas… Things 
are often much more complicated than you think. 

73
00:05:54,160 --> 00:05:58,720
Michelson did this experiment in 1881.
He was a very young man, and then other people,  

74
00:05:58,720 --> 00:06:02,320
I think Rayleigh was one of them, pointed out that 
there were some problems with the way he did it,  

75
00:06:02,320 --> 00:06:08,400
so they had to redo it in 1887.
At that point, a lot of the leading  

76
00:06:08,400 --> 00:06:16,640
physicists of the day basically accepted 
this result, that there was no ether wind. 

77
00:06:16,640 --> 00:06:20,880
But what to do about this?
Sure, maybe you falsified  

78
00:06:20,880 --> 00:06:23,200
some theories of the ether.
There are others that you  

79
00:06:23,200 --> 00:06:28,640
haven't falsified at all at this point, 
and people set to work on developing those. 

80
00:06:29,200 --> 00:06:34,160
It is funny, people will phrase it as 
showing that the ether didn't exist. 

81
00:06:34,160 --> 00:06:40,640
Even just the word "the" there is a misnomer.
You actually had a ton of different theories  

82
00:06:40,640 --> 00:06:45,600
and a couple of leading contenders.
So yes, there's some version of  

83
00:06:45,600 --> 00:06:53,200
falsification going on, but how you respond 
to this new experiment is very complicated. 

84
00:06:54,960 --> 00:06:59,600
Certainly the leading physicists of the day 
responded by saying, "Okay, this gives us a  

85
00:06:59,600 --> 00:07:04,160
lot of information about what the ether must be, 
but it doesn't tell us that there is no ether." 

86
00:07:04,160 --> 00:07:10,240
In fact, Lorentz at the end of 
the 19th century, before Einstein,  

87
00:07:10,240 --> 00:07:15,920
figures out the math of how you convert from 
one reference frame to another reference frame,  

88
00:07:15,920 --> 00:07:20,640
and comes up with the Lorentz transformations, 
which is the basis of special relativity. 

89
00:07:20,640 --> 00:07:25,600
But his interpretation is that you are 
converting from the ether reference  

90
00:07:25,600 --> 00:07:30,000
frame to these non-privileged other reference 
frames if you're moving relative to the ether. 

91
00:07:30,560 --> 00:07:36,560
His interpretation of length contraction and time 
dilation is that this is the effect of moving  

92
00:07:36,560 --> 00:07:42,080
through the ether, and you have this pressure. 
This pressure is warping clocks. It's warping  

93
00:07:43,760 --> 00:07:50,720
measures of length. The interesting thing here 
is that experimentally you cannot distinguish  

94
00:07:50,720 --> 00:07:58,080
Lorentz's interpretation from special relativity.
I think that's a strong statement. 

95
00:08:00,240 --> 00:08:05,840
Lorentz introduces this quantity called 
local time, which he regards as... 

96
00:08:06,800 --> 00:08:11,680
My understanding is he's not trying to 
give a physical interpretation of this,  

97
00:08:11,680 --> 00:08:17,680
but it's what Einstein would later just recognize 
as time in another inertial reference frame. 

98
00:08:18,320 --> 00:08:20,480
He's not trying to attribute 
much physical meaning to it. 

99
00:08:20,480 --> 00:08:25,040
I think Poincaré gets much closer 
later on to realizing that this  

100
00:08:25,040 --> 00:08:35,120
is the time that's registered by clocks.
About forty-odd years later, people start  

101
00:08:35,120 --> 00:08:40,160
doing these muon experiments where they see 
cosmic rays hit the top of the atmosphere. 

102
00:08:40,160 --> 00:08:45,760
They produce a shower of muons, and you can look 
to see at different heights in the atmosphere how  

103
00:08:45,760 --> 00:08:52,000
many of those muons remain.
They decay over time,  

104
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:56,880
and a very strange thing happens, which 
is that they're decaying way too slow. 

105
00:08:57,520 --> 00:09:03,120
You expect they shouldn't be able to last 
the whole way through the atmosphere at all. 

106
00:09:05,120 --> 00:09:10,240
Their decay rate is too quick, if 
you were in a classical theory. 

107
00:09:10,240 --> 00:09:16,080
But if in fact their time really 
has slowed down, it's okay. 

108
00:09:16,080 --> 00:09:21,200
In fact, the measured decay rates in 
1940—and there have since been more  

109
00:09:21,200 --> 00:09:26,320
accurate experiments done—match exactly 
what you expect from special relativity. 

110
00:09:28,160 --> 00:09:34,000
That's the kind of thing where if Lorentz had 
been alive—he'd been dead ten or so years at that  

111
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:41,280
point—it seems quite likely that he would have 
tried to save his theory by patching it up yet  

112
00:09:41,280 --> 00:09:48,640
again, but it would have been a massive setback.
It starts to just look like time—this  

113
00:09:50,880 --> 00:09:53,280
thing that Lorentz introduced as 
a mathematical convenience—that's  

114
00:09:53,840 --> 00:09:58,560
actually what time is, for the muons at least.
Then there's a whole bunch of other experiments  

115
00:09:58,560 --> 00:10:01,680
that show this very similar phenomenon.
When was that experiment done? 

116
00:10:01,680 --> 00:10:04,800
That was, I think, 1940. It might 
have been published in 1941. 

117
00:10:05,440 --> 00:10:12,880
Maybe to rephrase and change my claim: it's 
not that you could not have distinguished them,  

118
00:10:12,880 --> 00:10:17,520
but the scientific community adopted what 
we in retrospect consider the more correct  

119
00:10:17,520 --> 00:10:25,200
interpretation before it was actually 
experimentally shown to be preferred. 

120
00:10:25,200 --> 00:10:29,520
So there's clearly some process that human science 
does which can distinguish different theories. 

121
00:10:29,520 --> 00:10:36,240
Can I just interrupt? You used the word process, 
and it's interesting to think about that term. 

122
00:10:36,240 --> 00:10:41,360
Process carries connotations 
of something set in advance. 

123
00:10:43,280 --> 00:10:48,800
It's much more complicated in practice.
You have people like Lorentz, who Einstein  

124
00:10:49,600 --> 00:10:56,640
absolutely and utterly admired, and Poincaré, 
one of the greatest scientists who ever lived,  

125
00:10:57,760 --> 00:11:02,960
and Michelson, another truly outstanding 
scientist, who never reconciled themselves. 

126
00:11:02,960 --> 00:11:07,520
It's not as though there's some standard procedure 
that we're all using to reconcile these things. 

127
00:11:08,240 --> 00:11:14,320
Great scientists can remain wrong for a very 
long time after the scientific community has  

128
00:11:14,320 --> 00:11:18,000
broadly changed its opinion.
But there's no centralized  

129
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:24,400
authority or centralized method.
That is the interesting thing. There's  

130
00:11:24,400 --> 00:11:30,160
progress even though it is hard to articulate the 
process by which it happens, the heuristics that  

131
00:11:30,160 --> 00:11:37,200
are used. You mentioned Poincaré. Lorentz has 
the math right, but the interpretation wrong. 

132
00:11:38,800 --> 00:11:43,600
It seems like Poincaré had the opposite, where he 
understood that it's hard to define simultaneity  

133
00:11:44,160 --> 00:11:51,440
because it requires a circular definition with 
time, or velocity of something that might arrive  

134
00:11:51,440 --> 00:11:56,960
at a midpoint together, but velocity is defined in 
terms of time. I find this interesting. There are  

135
00:11:56,960 --> 00:12:01,200
a couple of other examples we could call on.
There is this phenomenon in the history of  

136
00:12:01,200 --> 00:12:07,040
science where somebody asks the right 
question, but then they don't clinch it. 

137
00:12:07,040 --> 00:12:09,520
I'm curious what you think 
is happening in those cases. 

138
00:12:11,840 --> 00:12:14,800
You actually do want to go case 
by case and try to understand. 

139
00:12:14,800 --> 00:12:18,800
It's not necessarily clear that they're 
doing the same thing wrong in all of the  

140
00:12:18,800 --> 00:12:24,880
cases. The Poincaré case is amazing. He seems 
to have understood the principle of relativity,  

141
00:12:24,880 --> 00:12:28,240
the idea that the laws of physics are the 
same in all inertial reference frames. 

142
00:12:28,240 --> 00:12:31,040
He seems to have understood 
that the speed of light is  

143
00:12:31,040 --> 00:12:36,480
the same in all inertial reference frames.
He doesn't phrase it quite that way, but it is  

144
00:12:36,480 --> 00:12:44,560
my understanding, though I don't speak French.
These are basically the ideas that Einstein  

145
00:12:44,560 --> 00:12:49,600
uses to deduce special relativity.
But then he also has this additional  

146
00:12:49,600 --> 00:12:56,640
misunderstanding where he thinks that length 
contraction is a dynamical effect, that somehow  

147
00:12:58,400 --> 00:13:04,960
particles are being pushed together by some 
external force, something is going on dynamically. 

148
00:13:04,960 --> 00:13:11,520
He doesn't understand that it's purely kinematics.
That actually space and time are different from  

149
00:13:11,520 --> 00:13:14,560
what we thought, and you need to 
fundamentally rethink those things. 

150
00:13:15,280 --> 00:13:22,720
It's almost like he knew too much.
He had almost too grand a vision in mind. 

151
00:13:22,720 --> 00:13:29,200
Einstein subtracts from that and says, "No.
Space and time are just different than what we  

152
00:13:29,200 --> 00:13:36,240
thought, and here's the correct picture."
There's a paper in, I think it's 1909,  

153
00:13:36,240 --> 00:13:43,200
where Poincaré still has this dynamical picture 
of what's going on with the length contraction.  

154
00:13:44,800 --> 00:13:51,520
This is just not necessary. This is a mistake 
from the modern point of view. Why is he doing  

155
00:13:51,520 --> 00:13:58,560
this? Why is he clinging onto this idea? I 
don't know. I've obviously never met the man. 

156
00:13:59,920 --> 00:14:03,520
It would be fascinating to be able to 
talk it over and try and understand. 

157
00:14:05,360 --> 00:14:13,840
His expertise seems to be getting in the way.
He knows so much, he understands so much,  

158
00:14:13,840 --> 00:14:20,640
and then he's not able to let go of these things.
A really interesting fact is that a few years  

159
00:14:20,640 --> 00:14:26,720
prior, in the 1890s, Einstein's a teenager 
and he believes in the ether too. He knows  

160
00:14:26,720 --> 00:14:34,160
about this stuff. But he's not quite 
as attached as these older people were. 

161
00:14:34,960 --> 00:14:38,960
Maybe they were a little bit prisoners of 
their own expertise. That's my guess. Some  

162
00:14:38,960 --> 00:14:45,680
historians of science would certainly disagree.
Then there's the obvious stories where Einstein  

163
00:14:45,680 --> 00:14:53,680
himself later on is said to have not latched onto 
the correct interpretations of quantum mechanics  

164
00:14:53,680 --> 00:14:57,200
or cosmology because of his own attachments.
Yeah. 

165
00:14:57,200 --> 00:15:02,800
Here’s the bigger question I have.
The muon example is a great example of  

166
00:15:04,480 --> 00:15:09,760
these long verification loops and how progress 
seems to happen in the scientific community  

167
00:15:09,760 --> 00:15:15,840
faster than these verification loops imply.
Maybe the clearest example is Aristarchus  

168
00:15:15,840 --> 00:15:20,400
in the second century BC comes up 
with the idea of heliocentrism. 

169
00:15:20,400 --> 00:15:24,320
The ancient Athenians dismiss it on the 
grounds that we should see as the Earth  

170
00:15:24,320 --> 00:15:27,120
is moving around the Sun, if really the 
Sun is the center of the solar system,  

171
00:15:27,120 --> 00:15:31,520
the stars move relative to the Earth.
The only reason that would not be the  

172
00:15:31,520 --> 00:15:35,200
case is the stars are so far away 
that you would not observe this. 

173
00:15:35,200 --> 00:15:40,080
And it's only in 1838 that stellar 
parallax was actually measured. 

174
00:15:40,080 --> 00:15:44,480
And so, we didn't need to wait 
until 1838 to have heliocentrism. 

175
00:15:44,480 --> 00:15:47,200
We didn't need to wait for 
the experimental validation to  

176
00:15:47,200 --> 00:15:53,920
understand that Copernicus is better in some way.
In fact, when Copernicus first came up  

177
00:15:53,920 --> 00:15:59,600
with his theories, it's well known that the 
Ptolemaic model was more accurate because it  

178
00:15:59,600 --> 00:16:05,440
had centuries of adding on these epicycles.
What's maybe less well appreciated is that it  

179
00:16:05,440 --> 00:16:10,400
was also in some sense simpler.
Because Copernicus actually  

180
00:16:10,400 --> 00:16:12,720
had to add extra epicycles.
It had more epicycles than the  

181
00:16:12,720 --> 00:16:20,720
Ptolemaic model because he had this bias that the 
Earth should go in a perfect circle in equal time. 

182
00:16:20,720 --> 00:16:26,000
Anyway, I think this is an interesting story 
because it's not a more accurate theory. It's  

183
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:30,960
not a simpler theory. So how 
could you have known ex ante  

184
00:16:30,960 --> 00:16:38,160
that Copernicus was correct and Ptolemy was not?
Good question. I don't entirely know the answer. 

185
00:16:41,680 --> 00:16:49,840
I can give you a partial answer that I, centuries 
in the future, start to find very compelling. 

186
00:16:52,320 --> 00:16:59,520
I'm sure it's part of the historic story at least.
One of the big shocks for Newton,  

187
00:17:01,360 --> 00:17:07,920
he did understand Kepler's laws of motion 
eventually, so you're able to explain the  

188
00:17:07,920 --> 00:17:12,800
motions of the planets in the sky.
But he also, out of the same theory,  

189
00:17:12,800 --> 00:17:16,160
his theory of gravitation, was 
able to explain terrestrial motion. 

190
00:17:16,160 --> 00:17:20,800
He's able to explain why objects move in 
parabolas on the Earth, and he's able to explain  

191
00:17:20,800 --> 00:17:31,040
the tides in terms of the moon and the sun's 
gravitational effect on water on the Earth. 

192
00:17:31,680 --> 00:17:37,840
You have what seem like three very different 
disconnected phenomena all being explained by  

193
00:17:37,840 --> 00:17:42,800
this one set of ideas.
That starts to feel  

194
00:17:42,800 --> 00:17:48,000
very compelling, at least to me.
I think most people find that very  

195
00:17:48,000 --> 00:17:53,520
satisfying once they eventually realize it.
Have you read the Keynes biography of Newton? 

196
00:17:54,400 --> 00:17:57,840
He wrote an entire biography?
No, the essay. 

197
00:17:57,840 --> 00:18:04,240
Sure. I love that. This description of him 
as the last of the magicians is wonderful. 

198
00:18:05,280 --> 00:18:09,280
In fact, I think it's maybe worth superimposing.
Or you should read out that one  

199
00:18:09,280 --> 00:18:17,120
passage of the thing.
Alright. It's from a talk  

200
00:18:17,120 --> 00:18:26,720
that he gave at Cambridge not long before he died.
He'd acquired Newton's papers somehow and gave a  

201
00:18:26,720 --> 00:18:32,640
lecture twice about this, or his brother Jeffrey 
gave it the other time because he was too ill. 

202
00:18:33,600 --> 00:18:36,160
There's this wonderful, 
wonderful quote in the middle. 

203
00:18:36,880 --> 00:18:41,760
The whole thing is really interesting, 
but I love this particular quote:  

204
00:18:41,760 --> 00:18:46,320
"Newton was not the first of the age of reason.
He was the last of the magicians, the last  

205
00:18:46,320 --> 00:18:50,640
great mind which looked out on the visible and 
intellectual world with the same eyes as those  

206
00:18:50,640 --> 00:18:55,600
who began to build our intellectual inheritance 
rather less than ten thousand years ago." 

207
00:18:56,880 --> 00:19:05,120
This idea people have that Newton was the 
first modern scientist is somehow wrong. 

208
00:19:07,360 --> 00:19:12,720
There's some truth to it, but he really 
had this very different way of looking  

209
00:19:12,720 --> 00:19:19,440
at the world that was part superstitious 
and part modern. It was a funny hybrid.  

210
00:19:19,440 --> 00:19:27,280
He's a transitional figure in some sense.
That phrase, "the last of the magicians,"  

211
00:19:27,920 --> 00:19:30,400
really points at something.
The thing I'm very curious  

212
00:19:30,400 --> 00:19:34,960
about with Newton is whether it was 
the same program, the same heuristics,  

213
00:19:34,960 --> 00:19:43,360
the same biases that he applied to his alchemical 
work as he did to his understanding of astronomy. 

214
00:19:43,360 --> 00:19:47,120
This is from the Keynes essay: "There 
was extreme method in his madness. 

215
00:19:47,120 --> 00:19:50,400
All his unpublished works on esoteric 
and theological matters are marked by  

216
00:19:50,400 --> 00:19:54,160
careful learning, accurate method, 
and extreme sobriety of statement. 

217
00:19:54,160 --> 00:19:59,440
They are just as sane as the Principia if their 
whole matter and purpose were not magical. 

218
00:19:59,440 --> 00:20:04,400
They were nearly all composed during the 
same 25 years of his mathematical studies." 

219
00:20:06,000 --> 00:20:12,240
Clearly, there was some aesthetic that motivated 
people like Einstein to reject earlier ways of  

220
00:20:12,240 --> 00:20:16,080
thinking and say, "No, the other is wrong, and 
there's a better way to think about things." 

221
00:20:16,080 --> 00:20:24,480
The same is true with Newton.
The question I have is whether  

222
00:20:24,480 --> 00:20:32,000
similar heuristics toward parsimony, 
aesthetics, and so on, would be equally  

223
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:37,440
useful across time and across disciplines, 
or whether you need different heuristics. 

224
00:20:37,440 --> 00:20:41,600
The reason that's relevant is even if we 
can't build a verification loop for science,  

225
00:20:41,600 --> 00:20:46,160
maybe if the taste tests point in the same 
direction, you can at least encode that bias  

226
00:20:46,160 --> 00:20:54,720
into the AIs. That would maybe be enough.
The point is that where we always get  

227
00:20:54,720 --> 00:21:00,560
bottlenecked is where the previous 
processes and heuristics don't apply. 

228
00:21:01,360 --> 00:21:05,440
That's almost definitionally 
what causes the bottlenecks. 

229
00:21:05,440 --> 00:21:09,760
Because people are smart, they know what 
has worked before. They study it. They apply  

230
00:21:09,760 --> 00:21:14,080
the same kinds of things, so they don't 
get stuck in the same places as before. 

231
00:21:14,080 --> 00:21:18,240
They keep getting bottlenecked 
in different places. 

232
00:21:18,800 --> 00:21:22,640
I'm overgeneralizing a bit, 
but I think it's right. 

233
00:21:22,640 --> 00:21:27,600
If you're attempting to reduce science to 
a process, you're attempting to reduce it  

234
00:21:27,600 --> 00:21:30,960
to something where there is just a 
method which you can apply, and you  

235
00:21:31,760 --> 00:21:37,520
turn the crank and out pops insight.
You can do a certain amount of that,  

236
00:21:37,520 --> 00:21:42,000
but you're going to get bottlenecked at the 
places where your existing method doesn't apply. 

237
00:21:43,760 --> 00:21:51,680
Definitionally, there's no crank you can turn.
You need a lot of people trying different ideas. 

238
00:21:53,360 --> 00:21:57,520
The more difficult the idea is to 
have, the greater the bottleneck,  

239
00:21:57,520 --> 00:22:02,320
but then also the greater the triumph.
Quantum mechanics is a great example of this. 

240
00:22:02,320 --> 00:22:07,920
It's such a shocking set of ideas. It's such 
a shocking theory. The theory of evolution in  

241
00:22:07,920 --> 00:22:15,760
some sense is also quite a shocking idea, not the 
principle of natural selection, but that it can  

242
00:22:15,760 --> 00:22:21,120
explain so much. That's a shocking idea.
Existing safety benchmarks claim that,  

243
00:22:21,120 --> 00:22:26,080
at least for today's top models, attacks are 
only successful a few percent of the time. 

244
00:22:26,080 --> 00:22:30,640
This sounds great, but Labelbox researchers 
were able to jailbreak these very same models  

245
00:22:30,640 --> 00:22:35,120
about 90% of the time – even the ones that 
have the strongest reputation for safety. 

246
00:22:35,120 --> 00:22:38,880
And the disconnect here is that the 
prompts which underlie these public safety  

247
00:22:38,880 --> 00:22:44,800
benchmarks are all framed in a very naive way.
There's no attempt to disguise harmful intent. 

248
00:22:44,800 --> 00:22:47,680
These prompts will just ask models 
to “hack into a secure network”  

249
00:22:47,680 --> 00:22:51,760
and to “do so without getting caught”.
But real bad actors don't write like this. 

250
00:22:51,760 --> 00:22:55,360
So Labelbox built a new safety 
benchmark from the ground up. 

251
00:22:55,360 --> 00:23:00,320
Their prompts reflect real adversarial behavior 
by stripping out obvious trigger phrases and  

252
00:23:00,320 --> 00:23:04,800
wrapping their request in fictional scenarios.
For example, instead of outright asking an LLM  

253
00:23:04,800 --> 00:23:07,680
to steal somebody's identity, the 
prompt will frame it as a game. 

254
00:23:07,680 --> 00:23:11,600
A light bearer who's trying to hide 
from dark forces needs a handbook  

255
00:23:11,600 --> 00:23:16,960
on how to disguise themselves as somebody else.
This safety research is linked in the description. 

256
00:23:16,960 --> 00:23:26,160
If you think this could be useful for your 
own work, reach out at labelbox.com/dwarkesh. 

257
00:23:26,160 --> 00:23:31,840
So Principia Mathematica is released in 1687.
The Origin of Species is released in 1859. 

258
00:23:33,120 --> 00:23:38,720
At least naively, it seems like Darwin's 
theory of natural selection is conceptually  

259
00:23:38,720 --> 00:23:45,600
easier than the theory of gravity.
I asked Terence Tao this question. 

260
00:23:46,400 --> 00:23:49,520
There was this contemporaneous 
biologist with Darwin, Thomas Huxley,  

261
00:23:49,520 --> 00:23:54,320
who read this and said, "How extremely 
stupid to not have thought of this." 

262
00:23:54,960 --> 00:23:59,040
Nobody ever reads the Principia Mathematica 
and thinks, "God, why didn't I beat Newton to  

263
00:23:59,040 --> 00:24:06,480
the punch here?" So what's going on here? 
Why did Darwinism take so much longer? 

264
00:24:07,280 --> 00:24:13,120
The idea must have been known to animal 
breeders for a long time at some level,  

265
00:24:15,040 --> 00:24:20,480
or certainly large chunks of the idea were 
known, that artificial selection was a thing. 

266
00:24:23,280 --> 00:24:29,280
In some sense, Darwin's genius 
wasn't in having that idea, it was  

267
00:24:29,280 --> 00:24:39,280
understanding just how central it was to biology.
You can go back and explain a tremendous amount  

268
00:24:39,280 --> 00:24:46,400
about all the variety of what we see in the world 
with this as not necessarily the only principle,  

269
00:24:46,400 --> 00:24:51,120
but certainly a core principle.
He writes this wonderful book,  

270
00:24:52,080 --> 00:24:57,520
The Origin of Species.
It's just so much evidence and  

271
00:24:57,520 --> 00:25:04,640
so many examples, trying to tease this 
out and see what the implications are,  

272
00:25:04,640 --> 00:25:14,800
and connecting it to as much else as he possibly 
can, to geology and all these other things. 

273
00:25:15,600 --> 00:25:21,200
That hard work—making the case that 
it's actually relevant all across the  

274
00:25:21,200 --> 00:25:25,840
biosphere—is what he's doing there.
He's not just having the idea,  

275
00:25:25,840 --> 00:25:30,640
he's making a compelling case that it's 
intertwined with absolutely everything else. 

276
00:25:30,640 --> 00:25:37,440
The motivation for the question was Lucretius, 
this first-century Roman poet who has an idea  

277
00:25:37,440 --> 00:25:42,720
that seems analogous to natural selection.
It's about species getting fitted more over  

278
00:25:42,720 --> 00:25:45,440
time to their environments, or species 
losing fit to their environment. 

279
00:25:46,080 --> 00:25:50,480
And so, why did this go 
nowhere for nineteen centuries? 

280
00:25:51,120 --> 00:25:56,400
Then I looked into it or, more accurately, asked 
LLMs what exactly Lucretius's idea here was. 

281
00:25:56,400 --> 00:25:59,920
It is extremely different from 
what real natural selection is. 

282
00:25:59,920 --> 00:26:03,600
He thought there was this generative period 
in the past where all the species came about,  

283
00:26:03,600 --> 00:26:07,680
and then there was this one-time filter which 
resulted in the species that are around today,  

284
00:26:07,680 --> 00:26:10,480
and they became fit to the environment.
He did not have this idea that it is an  

285
00:26:10,480 --> 00:26:16,480
ongoing gradual process or that there 
is a tree of life that connects all  

286
00:26:17,200 --> 00:26:18,880
life forms on Earth together, which, by the way,  

287
00:26:18,880 --> 00:26:23,280
is an incredibly weird fact that every single 
life form on Earth has a common ancestor. 

288
00:26:23,280 --> 00:26:29,680
It's not incredibly weird. If you think that 
the origin of life must have been very hard,  

289
00:26:29,680 --> 00:26:32,160
that there's a bottleneck there, 
then it's not so surprising. 

290
00:26:32,720 --> 00:26:38,880
There's also this verification loop aspect where 
even if Newton might be harder in some sense, if  

291
00:26:38,880 --> 00:26:44,320
you've clinched it, you can experimentally… I know 
"validate" is the wrong word philosophically, but  

292
00:26:44,320 --> 00:26:48,240
you can give a lot of base points to the theory.
You can be like, "Okay, I have this idea  

293
00:26:48,240 --> 00:26:50,720
of why things fall on Earth.
I have this idea of why orbital  

294
00:26:50,720 --> 00:26:54,800
periods for planets have a certain pattern.
Let's try it on the Moon, which orbits the Earth." 

295
00:26:54,800 --> 00:26:58,800
And in fact, it’s weird but the orbital 
period matches what my calculations imply. 

296
00:26:58,800 --> 00:27:05,280
And the tides work correctly. It's just amazing.
Exactly. Whereas for Darwinism, it takes a ton  

297
00:27:05,280 --> 00:27:08,800
of work for Darwin to compile all the 
cumulative evidence, but there's no  

298
00:27:08,800 --> 00:27:12,720
individual piece that is overwhelmingly powerful.
And there's a whole bunch of problems as well. 

299
00:27:12,720 --> 00:27:16,640
He doesn't really understand 
what the mechanism is. 

300
00:27:16,640 --> 00:27:20,400
He doesn't understand genes, all these things.
The very interesting thing in the history of  

301
00:27:20,400 --> 00:27:29,440
Darwinism is, this idea which theoretically you 
could come up with at any time, there is almost  

302
00:27:29,440 --> 00:27:33,600
identical independent creation of that idea 
between Alfred Wallace and Charles Darwin. 

303
00:27:34,400 --> 00:27:37,040
So much so that I think Wallace sends 
his manuscript to Darwin and is like,  

304
00:27:37,040 --> 00:27:40,800
"What do you think of this 
idea?" And Darwin's like, "Fuck." 

305
00:27:40,800 --> 00:27:43,760
I don't think that's an exact 
quote, but it's pretty much correct. 

306
00:27:44,720 --> 00:27:48,640
They end up presenting their ideas 
together in the spirit of sportsmanship. 

307
00:27:49,520 --> 00:27:53,520
Why was this period in the 1850s or 1860s 
the right time for these ideas to form? 

308
00:27:53,520 --> 00:28:00,560
You can come up with different ideas. One is 
geology. In the 1830s, Charles Lyell figures  

309
00:28:00,560 --> 00:28:04,720
out that there's been millions and billions 
of years of time that's existed on Earth. 

310
00:28:04,720 --> 00:28:10,880
The paleontology shows you that fossils 
have existed for that entire time. 

311
00:28:10,880 --> 00:28:12,560
Life goes back a long way.
In fact, you can even find  

312
00:28:12,560 --> 00:28:16,800
fossils for intermediate species 
that show you the tree of life. 

313
00:28:16,800 --> 00:28:20,080
Between humans and other apes as 
well, there's intermediate humans. 

314
00:28:20,880 --> 00:28:25,760
There's also the age of colonization, and we 
have all these voyages doing biogeography. 

315
00:28:27,680 --> 00:28:31,600
That all must have been necessary.
In fact, there's a huge history of  

316
00:28:31,600 --> 00:28:33,920
parallel innovation and discovery 
in the history of science. 

317
00:28:33,920 --> 00:28:37,920
So maybe it is another piece of 
evidence that more had to be in  

318
00:28:37,920 --> 00:28:41,360
place for a given idea to be discovered.
Because if it's not discovered for a long  

319
00:28:41,360 --> 00:28:46,080
time and then spontaneously many different people 
are coming up with it, that shows you that the  

320
00:28:46,080 --> 00:28:56,080
building blocks were in some sense necessary.
This example of Lyell and other geologists  

321
00:28:56,080 --> 00:29:02,560
in the early 1800s having this idea of 
deep time does seem to have been crucial. 

322
00:29:02,560 --> 00:29:13,920
I know Darwin was very influenced by Lyell.
If you don't have at least tens or hundreds  

323
00:29:13,920 --> 00:29:17,840
of millions of years, evolution 
starts to look like a non-starter. 

324
00:29:20,160 --> 00:29:27,040
In order to make it work on a timescale of 5,000 
to 10,000 years or 6,000 years with Bishop Ussher  

325
00:29:28,000 --> 00:29:34,320
you would need to see evolution occurring 
at a massive rate during human lifetimes,  

326
00:29:34,320 --> 00:29:37,600
and we're just not seeing that.
That does seem to have been a blocker. 

327
00:29:39,280 --> 00:29:47,360
To your question of what other blockers were 
there, were there any others? I don't know. 

328
00:29:47,360 --> 00:29:51,760
Or how much earlier could you, in principle, 
have come up with it if you were much smarter? 

329
00:29:52,400 --> 00:29:58,080
Let's go back and zoom out to your original 
question about the verification loop in AI. 

330
00:30:00,560 --> 00:30:06,000
An example that should give you pause 
there is the big signature success so  

331
00:30:06,000 --> 00:30:13,600
far, which is certainly AlphaFold. AlphaFold 
really isn't about AI. A massive fraction of  

332
00:30:13,600 --> 00:30:20,960
the success there is the Protein Data Bank.
It's X-ray diffraction, NMR, cryo-EM,  

333
00:30:20,960 --> 00:30:27,200
and the several billion dollars that were spent 
obtaining those 180,000-odd protein structures. 

334
00:30:28,720 --> 00:30:34,160
It's basically the story of how we spent 
many decades obtaining protein structure  

335
00:30:34,160 --> 00:30:38,480
just by going out and looking very hard 
at the world experimentally, and then we  

336
00:30:38,480 --> 00:30:42,880
fitted a nice model at the end of it, which 
was a tiny fraction of the entire investment. 

337
00:30:46,560 --> 00:30:52,160
That's a story of data acquisition principally.
The AI bit is very impressive and quite  

338
00:30:52,160 --> 00:30:56,640
remarkable, but it is only a 
small part of the total story. 

339
00:30:56,640 --> 00:31:00,080
AlphaFold is very interesting, and 
philosophically I wonder what you think  

340
00:31:00,080 --> 00:31:07,680
of it as a scientific theory or explanation.
I guess over time the world is becoming harder  

341
00:31:07,680 --> 00:31:16,400
to understand… As I'm saying things, because 
you're such a careful speaker, I say a phrase  

342
00:31:16,400 --> 00:31:25,760
and wonder if you'll actually buy that premise.
But in some domains, we need to fit models to  

343
00:31:25,760 --> 00:31:27,440
things rather than coming up 
with underlying principles  

344
00:31:27,440 --> 00:31:33,440
that explain a broad range of phenomena.
Compare the theory of general relativity,  

345
00:31:35,040 --> 00:31:40,000
or any theory which just nets out to some 
equations, versus AlphaFold, which is encoding  

346
00:31:40,000 --> 00:31:46,720
these different relationships between things we 
can't even interpret over 100 million parameters. 

347
00:31:46,720 --> 00:31:53,040
Are those really the same thing?
GR can predict things you could  

348
00:31:53,040 --> 00:31:57,680
have never anticipated or it was never meant 
to do, like why Mercury's orbit precesses. 

349
00:31:58,560 --> 00:32:02,480
AlphaFold is not going to have 
that kind of explanatory reach. 

350
00:32:03,440 --> 00:32:07,200
I want to get your reaction to that.
I think it's an incredibly interesting  

351
00:32:07,200 --> 00:32:17,040
question. Maybe a really pivotal question. If you 
take a very classic point of view, you want these  

352
00:32:17,040 --> 00:32:21,360
deep explanatory principles.
You want as few free  

353
00:32:21,360 --> 00:32:27,120
parameters as you possibly can.
You want very simple models which explain a lot,  

354
00:32:27,120 --> 00:32:32,560
and AlphaFold doesn't look anything like that.
You might just say, "It's nice and maybe  

355
00:32:32,560 --> 00:32:36,640
helpful as a model, but it's 
not a scientific explanation." 

356
00:32:37,280 --> 00:32:42,480
That's a conservative point of 
view, answer one to the question. 

357
00:32:42,480 --> 00:32:51,600
Answer two is to say maybe you shouldn't 
think about AlphaFold as an explanation in  

358
00:32:51,600 --> 00:32:55,680
the classic sense, but maybe it contains 
lots of little explanations inside it. 

359
00:32:56,240 --> 00:33:00,880
Part of what you can get out of 
interpretability work is you can go into  

360
00:33:00,880 --> 00:33:07,520
AlphaFold and start to extract certain things.
Maybe by doing an archeology of AlphaFold,  

361
00:33:08,480 --> 00:33:12,400
we can actually understand a great 
deal more about these principles. 

362
00:33:12,400 --> 00:33:16,320
You can start to extract that a certain circuit 
does this interesting thing, and we learn from it. 

363
00:33:16,880 --> 00:33:20,560
I don't know to what extent that's been done with 
AlphaFold, but it's been done a little bit with  

364
00:33:22,400 --> 00:33:28,480
some of the chess models, like AlphaZero.
There seem to be some strategies which  

365
00:33:28,480 --> 00:33:35,600
