368
00:33:49,440 --> 00:33:55,840
That's an example where human beings are 
starting to extract meaning out of these models. 

369
00:33:55,840 --> 00:34:01,040
That leads to viewing the models as 
a potential source of explanations. 

370
00:34:01,040 --> 00:34:04,160
You need to do more work because 
they're not very legible up front,  

371
00:34:04,160 --> 00:34:09,600
but you can potentially extract them.
That's an interesting intermediate  

372
00:34:10,160 --> 00:34:13,520
situation where they're not explanations 
themselves, but you can extract interesting  

373
00:34:13,520 --> 00:34:20,240
explanations out of them and use them as a source.
The third and most interesting possibility is  

374
00:34:20,240 --> 00:34:25,200
that they're a new type of object.
They should be taken very seriously  

375
00:34:25,200 --> 00:34:30,880
as explanations, but where in the past we haven't 
had the ability to really do anything with them,  

376
00:34:30,880 --> 00:34:37,360
now we have interesting new actions we can do.
We can merge them, we can distill them. 

377
00:34:41,200 --> 00:34:45,280
It's a big opportunity in 
the philosophy of science. 

378
00:34:48,080 --> 00:34:58,400
There's an anticipation of this in some way.
Some mathematicians and physicists work today…  

379
00:34:58,400 --> 00:35:05,840
Historically, if you had a 100-page equation—which 
is the kind of thing that does come up—there's  

380
00:35:05,840 --> 00:35:11,760
just nothing you can do if it's 1920.
At that point, you give up on the problem. 

381
00:35:11,760 --> 00:35:16,400
But today, with tools like 
Mathematica, you can just keep going. 

382
00:35:18,000 --> 00:35:21,280
That's an object now, a 
thing that you can work with. 

383
00:35:21,280 --> 00:35:25,120
There are examples where people work with 
these things that formerly were regarded  

384
00:35:25,120 --> 00:35:28,320
as too complicated, and sometimes 
they get simple answers out the end. 

385
00:35:28,320 --> 00:35:33,840
That’s just an intermediate working state.
So I wonder if something similar is going to  

386
00:35:33,840 --> 00:35:43,920
happen in this case, where you could take these 
models and use them in a similar way that people  

387
00:35:43,920 --> 00:35:48,960
do with Mathematica, and take them seriously.
They're not explanations in the classic sense,  

388
00:35:48,960 --> 00:35:54,400
but they'll be something else which 
interesting operations can be done on. 

389
00:35:54,400 --> 00:36:03,920
The thing I worry about is, suppose it's 
1500 and you're training a model on… This  

390
00:36:03,920 --> 00:36:08,080
is a weird history where we developed 
deep learning before we had cosmology. 

391
00:36:08,880 --> 00:36:13,200
Suppose we live in that world.
You're observing how the stars don't seem to move. 

392
00:36:13,200 --> 00:36:18,880
The planets have all these weird behaviors.
Then you train a model on that, and you do  

393
00:36:18,880 --> 00:36:22,480
some kind of interp on it trying to 
figure out what the patterns are. 

394
00:36:22,480 --> 00:36:26,640
You'd just be able to keep 
building on Ptolemy's model. 

395
00:36:26,640 --> 00:36:28,880
You'd see there's another 
epicycle we didn't notice. 

396
00:36:31,760 --> 00:36:37,120
Parameters X to Y encode this epicycle, 
parameters whatever encode the next epicycle. 

397
00:36:37,120 --> 00:36:41,520
If you were just trying to figure out 
why the solar system is the way it is  

398
00:36:41,520 --> 00:36:45,200
from observational data, you could just 
keep adding epicycles upon epicycles,  

399
00:36:45,200 --> 00:36:52,240
but it really took one mind to integrate it all in 
and say, "Here's what makes more sense overall." 

400
00:36:56,960 --> 00:37:02,400
This is to my point that we don't really 
understand what to do with the models. 

401
00:37:03,440 --> 00:37:08,000
We don't have the verbs yet.
It is certainly interesting  

402
00:37:08,000 --> 00:37:13,600
to think about the question where you 
start to apply constraints to the models,  

403
00:37:14,480 --> 00:37:19,200
essentially saying, "What's the simplest 
possible explanation?" Or, "Can you  

404
00:37:19,200 --> 00:37:28,240
simplify? Can you give me the 90/10 explanation?"
And go further and further in boiling it down. 

405
00:37:28,240 --> 00:37:31,120
It might be that indeed they 
start out by providing a very,  

406
00:37:31,120 --> 00:37:38,800
very complicated, many-parameter model.
But you can just force the case, and basically  

407
00:37:38,800 --> 00:37:47,680
that's scaffolding, which maybe is the very early 
days of their attempt to understand something. 

408
00:37:48,720 --> 00:37:52,080
They're forced through that to a 
much more simple understanding. 

409
00:37:52,640 --> 00:37:54,960
Sorry for misunderstanding, but it sounds 
like you're saying maybe there's some  

410
00:37:54,960 --> 00:38:02,400
regularizer or some distillation you could do of 
a very complicated model that gets you to a truer,  

411
00:38:02,400 --> 00:38:09,360
more parsimonious theory. Take Ptolemy versus 
Copernicus. You start off with lots of Ptolemy  

412
00:38:09,360 --> 00:38:15,520
epicycles, and then you try to distill this 
model, and maybe it gets rid of some of the  

413
00:38:15,520 --> 00:38:22,160
epicycles that are less and less necessary to get 
the mean squared error of the orbits to match. 

414
00:38:22,160 --> 00:38:25,600
But at some point it has to do this 
thing which is to switch two things. 

415
00:38:26,960 --> 00:38:29,360
Locally, it actually doesn't 
make things more accurate. 

416
00:38:29,360 --> 00:38:32,960
It's in a global sense that 
it's a more progressive theory. 

417
00:38:34,560 --> 00:38:38,240
There's some process which obviously 
humanity did over its span, which did  

418
00:38:38,240 --> 00:38:42,720
that regularization or did that swap.
But with raw gradient descent,  

419
00:38:43,600 --> 00:38:49,360
I don't really feel like it would do that.
Think about the example of going from  

420
00:38:49,360 --> 00:38:52,720
Newtonian gravity to Einstein's 
general theory of relativity. 

421
00:38:53,440 --> 00:39:00,160
These are shockingly different theories, 
and the question is what causes that flip. 

422
00:39:00,800 --> 00:39:06,560
As nearly as I understand the history, what goes 
on is Einstein develops special relativity and  

423
00:39:06,560 --> 00:39:13,120
pretty much straight away he understands. It's a 
very obvious observation. In special relativity,  

424
00:39:13,120 --> 00:39:17,120
influences can't propagate faster than 
the speed of light, and in Newtonian  

425
00:39:17,120 --> 00:39:24,320
gravity, action is at a distance.
Straight away in special relativity,  

426
00:39:24,320 --> 00:39:28,000
you could use Newtonian gravity 
to do faster-than-light signaling. 

427
00:39:28,000 --> 00:39:31,440
You could send information backwards in time.
You could do all kinds of crazy stuff. 

428
00:39:32,080 --> 00:39:39,360
It's not a big leap to realize we have 
a big problem here. That's the forcing  

429
00:39:39,360 --> 00:39:43,280
function there. You've realized that 
your old explanation is not sufficient.  

430
00:39:43,280 --> 00:39:50,640
You need something new. Then you're going to 
start by doing the simplest possible stuff. 

431
00:39:52,320 --> 00:40:00,960
It just turns out that a lot of that stuff 
doesn't work very well, so you're forced to go  

432
00:40:00,960 --> 00:40:07,920
through these steps where gradually it gets more 
complicated, and it's wrong in a variety of ways. 

433
00:40:08,640 --> 00:40:15,840
The final theory appears shockingly 
simple and beautiful, but it's gone  

434
00:40:15,840 --> 00:40:22,880
through some somewhat ugly intermediate stages.
If you're thinking about what it looks like to  

435
00:40:22,880 --> 00:40:28,880
have AI accelerate science, there's one for 
well-understood domains where we just want  

436
00:40:28,880 --> 00:40:33,840
local solutions, like how does this protein fold.
We just train a raw model using gradient descent. 

437
00:40:33,840 --> 00:40:37,520
Then there's things like coming up with general 
relativity, where you couldn't really just train  

438
00:40:37,520 --> 00:40:42,320
on every single observation in the universe 
and hope that general relativity pops out.  

439
00:40:44,400 --> 00:40:51,120
What would it require? It also certainly wasn't 
immediately discovered. It was decades of thought.  

440
00:40:52,800 --> 00:40:57,040
You'd need independent research programs where 
people start off with these biases, where Einstein  

441
00:40:57,040 --> 00:41:03,440
is initially motivated by this thought experiment 
of whether you can distinguish the effect of  

442
00:41:03,440 --> 00:41:10,640
gravity from just being accelerated upwards.
You just need different AI thinkers to start  

443
00:41:10,640 --> 00:41:13,680
off with these initial biases and 
see what can germinate out of them. 

444
00:41:14,320 --> 00:41:17,760
The verification loop for that might be quite 
long, but you just need to keep all those  

445
00:41:17,760 --> 00:41:24,080
research programs alive at the same time.
This point you make about keeping all  

446
00:41:24,080 --> 00:41:28,960
the different research programs alive, I 
think that is very important and central. 

447
00:41:30,720 --> 00:41:37,600
A great example is situations where the 
same answer has been correct in some  

448
00:41:37,600 --> 00:41:45,360
circumstances and wrong in other circumstances.
The planet Uranus was not in quite the right spot,  

449
00:41:45,360 --> 00:41:52,240
and people famously predicted the 
existence of Neptune on this basis. 

450
00:41:52,240 --> 00:41:58,400
Wonderful, massive success for Newtonian gravity.
The planet Mercury is not in quite the right spot. 

451
00:41:58,400 --> 00:42:02,560
You predict the existence of 
some other distorting planet. 

452
00:42:02,560 --> 00:42:06,880
It turns out that doesn't exist.
Actually, the reason Mercury is not in the right  

453
00:42:06,880 --> 00:42:13,360
spot is because you need general relativity.
You've pursued very similar ideas,  

454
00:42:13,360 --> 00:42:16,000
and it's been very successful in one 
case, and it's been completely and  

455
00:42:16,000 --> 00:42:20,880
utterly unsuccessful in the other case.
A priori, you can't tell which of these is the  

456
00:42:20,880 --> 00:42:27,760
thing to do, and you actually need to do both.
This is certainly very true in the  

457
00:42:27,760 --> 00:42:32,080
history of science.
This kind of diversity,  

458
00:42:32,080 --> 00:42:36,720
where you just have lots of people go off and 
pursue lots of potentially promising ideas,  

459
00:42:36,720 --> 00:42:42,320
you just need to support that for a long time.
It's hard to do that for a variety of reasons,  

460
00:42:42,960 --> 00:42:52,640
but it does seem to be very, very important.
This example of Uranus versus Mercury  

461
00:42:52,640 --> 00:42:57,120
is very interesting.
I think it illustrates  

462
00:42:57,120 --> 00:43:02,560
the difficulty with falsificationism.
The orbit of Uranus is in some sense  

463
00:43:02,560 --> 00:43:07,040
falsifying Newtonian mechanics.
But then you make some ancillary  

464
00:43:08,640 --> 00:43:12,560
prediction that says, "Oh, the reason this 
is happening is there must be another planet  

465
00:43:12,560 --> 00:43:18,800
which is perturbing Uranus's orbit."
I think it's Le Verrier in 1846.  

466
00:43:18,800 --> 00:43:20,960
"Point a telescope in the right 
direction, you find Uranus." 

467
00:43:20,960 --> 00:43:23,200
Neptune.
Sorry. Neptune,  

468
00:43:23,200 --> 00:43:29,840
yes. But with Mercury, it's observed that the 
ellipse which forms its orbit is rotating 43  

469
00:43:29,840 --> 00:43:34,560
arcseconds more every century than Newtonian 
mechanics would imply, so people say that  

470
00:43:34,560 --> 00:43:39,760
there must be a planet inside Mercury's orbit.
They call it Vulcan and point the telescopes.  

471
00:43:39,760 --> 00:43:44,400
It's not there. But if you're a proper Newtonian, 
what you do is say, "Well, maybe there's some  

472
00:43:44,400 --> 00:43:49,120
cosmic dust that's occluding this planet, or 
maybe the planet is so small we can't see it,  

473
00:43:49,120 --> 00:43:55,440
or let's build an even more powerful telescope, 
or maybe there's some magnetic field which is  

474
00:43:55,440 --> 00:43:56,560
occluding our measurement."
At any one of these steps— 

475
00:43:56,560 --> 00:44:00,240
And this happens over and over.
There are just so many stories  

476
00:44:00,240 --> 00:44:07,040
which are exactly like this.
An example I love from the 1990s. 

477
00:44:07,040 --> 00:44:11,120
Some people noticed that the Pioneer spacecraft 
weren't quite where they were supposed to be. 

478
00:44:11,920 --> 00:44:14,960
You can get very excited about this. "Oh 
my goodness, general relativity is wrong. 

479
00:44:16,640 --> 00:44:19,360
Maybe we're going to discover 
the next theory of gravity." 

480
00:44:20,560 --> 00:44:30,800
Today the accepted explanation is that there's 
just a slight asymmetry in the spacecraft. 

481
00:44:30,800 --> 00:44:35,760
It turns out that the thermal radiation 
is slightly larger in one direction than  

482
00:44:35,760 --> 00:44:39,280
the other, and that's causing a tiny 
little acceleration towards the sun. 

483
00:44:40,400 --> 00:44:44,320
Most of the time when there's 
these apparent exceptions,  

484
00:44:44,320 --> 00:44:50,080
it's just something like that going on.
It's very much like the Mercury-Vulcan case. 

485
00:44:50,800 --> 00:44:56,080
But every once in a while, it's not.
A priori, you can't distinguish these. 

486
00:44:56,080 --> 00:44:59,520
Science is just full of these.
It's funny too, the way we tell  

487
00:44:59,520 --> 00:45:06,640
the history of science, it sounds so simple.
You just focus on the right exception and  

488
00:45:07,520 --> 00:45:14,480
you realize that you need to throw out the old 
theory and lo and behold, your Nobel Prize awaits. 

489
00:45:14,480 --> 00:45:20,640
But in fact, these exceptions are all over the 
place. 99.9% of the time, it just turns out to be  

490
00:45:20,640 --> 00:45:25,600
some effect like this thermal acceleration 
in the case of the Pioneer spacecraft. 

491
00:45:28,000 --> 00:45:32,640
Unfortunately, there's a lot of 
selection bias going into those stories. 

492
00:45:32,640 --> 00:45:37,440
The thing is there's no ex ante heuristic 
which tells you which case you're in. 

493
00:45:38,720 --> 00:45:44,000
To spell out why I think this is important, some 
people have this idea that AI is going to make  

494
00:45:44,000 --> 00:45:49,520
disproportionate progress towards science because 
it makes disproportionate progress towards domains  

495
00:45:49,520 --> 00:45:52,240
where there's tight verification loops.
It's really good at coding because you  

496
00:45:52,240 --> 00:45:54,720
can run unit tests.
Science may be similar  

497
00:45:54,720 --> 00:45:59,600
because you can run experiments.
What that doesn't appreciate is that  

498
00:46:01,200 --> 00:46:03,920
there's an infinite number of theories that 
are compatible with any given experiment. 

499
00:46:04,960 --> 00:46:10,320
Over time, why we latch onto the one we 
think is more correct in retrospect is,  

500
00:46:10,320 --> 00:46:16,720
as we're discussing, hard to articulate.
Lakatos has all kinds of interesting examples  

501
00:46:16,720 --> 00:46:23,600
in the book about these hostile verification 
loops that are extremely long-lasting. 

502
00:46:24,480 --> 00:46:31,760
One he talks about is Prout.
There's this chemist in 1815 who hypothesizes that  

503
00:46:31,760 --> 00:46:38,560
all atomic nuclei must have whole number weights.
They're basically all made of hydrogen. 

504
00:46:38,560 --> 00:46:42,800
The reason he thinks this is because if you 
look at the measured weights of all elements,  

505
00:46:42,800 --> 00:46:45,920
it does seem that almost all of 
them have whole number weights. 

506
00:46:45,920 --> 00:46:51,440
But then there are some exceptions.
For example, chlorine comes out at 35.5. 

507
00:46:51,440 --> 00:46:55,840
So then there's all these ad hoc theories that 
people in this school keep coming up with, like,  

508
00:46:55,840 --> 00:46:59,760
"Oh, maybe there's chemical impurities."
But there's no chemical reaction you  

509
00:46:59,760 --> 00:47:03,040
can do which seems to get rid of this.
Maybe it's fractions of whole numbers,  

510
00:47:03,040 --> 00:47:05,360
so 35.5 can be halves.
But actually, if you  

511
00:47:05,360 --> 00:47:10,720
measure chlorine even closer, it's 35.46, so it's 
getting further away from the correct fraction. 

512
00:47:11,680 --> 00:47:15,040
Later on, what is discovered is what you're 
actually measuring is different isotopes,  

513
00:47:15,760 --> 00:47:19,680
which cannot be chemically distinguished.
They can only be physically distinguished. 

514
00:47:20,560 --> 00:47:25,280
So you have 85 years before we realize what 
an isotope is, where the verification loop is  

515
00:47:25,280 --> 00:47:30,800
actively hostile against the correct theory.
You just need this remnant to be defending…  

516
00:47:30,800 --> 00:47:32,560
There's no ex ante reason 
it's the preferred theory. 

517
00:47:33,200 --> 00:47:38,000
As a community, we should just have people 
try to integrate new observations, even if  

518
00:47:38,000 --> 00:47:45,760
they don't seem to fit their school of thought, 
and hopefully enough of that happens… Anyways,  

519
00:47:45,760 --> 00:47:51,200
I guess the thing I'm trying to articulate 
is the difficulty with automating science. 

520
00:47:51,200 --> 00:47:53,840
The question is, where is 
the bottleneck at some level? 

521
00:47:56,240 --> 00:47:59,680
Are we primarily bottlenecked 
on one type of thing, or are  

522
00:47:59,680 --> 00:48:07,200
we bottlenecked on multiple types of things?
Certainly, talking to structural biology people,  

523
00:48:07,200 --> 00:48:12,400
they seem to think that AlphaFold was an 
enormous advance. It was a shock. At some level,  

524
00:48:12,400 --> 00:48:22,160
yes, AI can certainly help us speed up science.
It is helping with a certain type of bottleneck. 

525
00:48:22,160 --> 00:48:24,800
That doesn't mean though, as you're 
saying, that it's necessarily going  

526
00:48:24,800 --> 00:48:29,440
to help with all kinds of bottlenecks.
I suppose the question you're pointing at is,  

527
00:48:29,440 --> 00:48:34,960
what are the types of bottlenecks that remain, 
and what are the prospects for getting past them? 

528
00:48:35,760 --> 00:48:40,640
Even in the case of coding, it's really 
interesting talking to programmer friends. 

529
00:48:40,640 --> 00:48:45,520
At the moment they're all in this 
state of shock and high excitement,  

530
00:48:45,520 --> 00:48:51,600
and they're all over the place.
You do wonder where the  

531
00:48:51,600 --> 00:48:54,320
bottleneck is going to move to.
Certainly, one thing that a lot  

532
00:48:54,320 --> 00:48:59,520
of them seem to be bottlenecked on now is 
having interesting ideas, and in particular,  

533
00:48:59,520 --> 00:49:04,000
having interesting design ideas.
There's not really a verification loop for  

534
00:49:04,000 --> 00:49:12,080
knowing that a design idea is very interesting.
They're no longer nearly as bottlenecked by their  

535
00:49:12,080 --> 00:49:16,160
ability to produce code, but they are 
still bottlenecked by this other thing. 

536
00:49:17,440 --> 00:49:22,960
Formerly, they weren't bottlenecked on it because 
just writing code took so much of their time. 

537
00:49:22,960 --> 00:49:28,560
They could have lots of ideas while they were 
taking three weeks to implement their prototype,  

538
00:49:28,560 --> 00:49:32,800
and then they would implement the next version.
Now they're taking three hours to implement the  

539
00:49:32,800 --> 00:49:39,040
prototype, and they don't have as good ideas 
after that, from a design point of view. 

540
00:49:39,040 --> 00:49:43,840
Last year, I predicted that by 2028, 
AI would be able to prep my taxes about  

541
00:49:43,840 --> 00:49:47,520
as well as a competent General Manager.
But we're already getting pretty close. 

542
00:49:47,520 --> 00:49:51,440
As I shared before, I use Mercury both 
for my business and my personal banking. 

543
00:49:51,440 --> 00:49:54,960
So I recently gave an LLM access 
to my transaction history across  

544
00:49:54,960 --> 00:50:00,000
both accounts through Mercury's MCP.
I asked it to go through all my 2025 transactions  

545
00:50:00,000 --> 00:50:04,880
and flag any personal expenses that seem like 
they should actually be charged to the business. 

546
00:50:04,880 --> 00:50:08,880
And this worked shockingly well.
Mercury's MCP exposes a bunch of  

547
00:50:08,880 --> 00:50:15,680
detailed information, things like notes and memos 
and any JPEGs of receipts and PDF attachments. 

548
00:50:15,680 --> 00:50:19,440
So my LLM had plenty of context to work with.
One of my favorite examples  

549
00:50:19,440 --> 00:50:22,960
happened with a charge to Bay Padel.
If you looked at the vendor alone, you would  

550
00:50:22,960 --> 00:50:28,560
have had to assume that it's a personal expense.
But the LLM looked at the receipt and the attached  

551
00:50:28,560 --> 00:50:32,560
note in Mercury and realized this 
was actually a team bonding exercise  

552
00:50:32,560 --> 00:50:36,560
from our last in-person retreat.
So a legitimate business expense. 

553
00:50:36,560 --> 00:50:40,320
I imagine it will be a while 
before traditional banks have MCP. 

554
00:50:40,320 --> 00:50:45,120
Functionality like this is why I use Mercury.
Go to mercury.com to learn more. 

555
00:50:45,120 --> 00:50:48,320
Mercury is a fintech company, 
not an FDIC Insured Bank. 

556
00:50:48,320 --> 00:50:54,320
Banking services provided through Choice 
Financial Group and Column NA, members FDIC. 

557
00:50:54,320 --> 00:50:58,000
You have a very interesting take.
I think it was a footnote in one of  

558
00:50:58,000 --> 00:51:02,160
your essays, and I couldn't find it again, 
which was that it's very possible that if  

559
00:51:02,160 --> 00:51:07,360
we met aliens, they would have a totally 
different technological stack than us. 

560
00:51:07,360 --> 00:51:11,680
That contradicts a common assumption I 
had that I never questioned, which is that  

561
00:51:11,680 --> 00:51:17,360
science is this thing you do relatively 
early on in the history of civilization. 

562
00:51:17,360 --> 00:51:21,680
You get to a point and you have a couple hundred 
years of just cranking through the basics,  

563
00:51:21,680 --> 00:51:27,520
understanding how the universe works, and you've 
got it. You've got science. Then everybody  

564
00:51:27,520 --> 00:51:31,360
would converge on the same "science."
I found that a very interesting idea,  

565
00:51:31,360 --> 00:51:39,840
and I want you to say more about it.
The idea there that I'm at least somewhat  

566
00:51:39,840 --> 00:51:48,880
attached to is that the tech tree or the 
science and tech tree is probably much  

567
00:51:48,880 --> 00:51:54,560
larger than we realize. We're in this funny 
situation. People will sometimes talk about  

568
00:51:55,600 --> 00:52:02,160
a theory of everything as a potential goal for 
physics, and then there's this presumption that  

569
00:52:02,160 --> 00:52:06,160
physics is done once you get there.
Of course, this is not true at all. 

570
00:52:06,160 --> 00:52:12,720
If you think about computer science, 
computer science started in the 1930s  

571
00:52:12,720 --> 00:52:18,080
when Turing and Church and so on laid 
down what the theory of everything was. 

572
00:52:18,080 --> 00:52:24,960
They just said, "Here's how computation works."
We've spent ninety-odd years since then  

573
00:52:24,960 --> 00:52:29,200
exploring the consequences of that and gradually 
building up more and more interesting ideas. 

574
00:52:29,760 --> 00:52:32,720
Those ideas, to some extent, 
you can regard as technology. 

575
00:52:32,720 --> 00:52:38,320
But insofar as they're discovered principles 
inside that theory of computation, I think  

576
00:52:38,320 --> 00:52:42,960
they're best regarded as science and in 
some cases, very fundamental science. 

577
00:52:42,960 --> 00:52:49,920
Ideas like public-key cryptography are 
incredibly deep, very non-obvious ideas which  

578
00:52:50,880 --> 00:52:59,680
lay hidden already in the 1930s.
My expectation is that there will  

579
00:52:59,680 --> 00:53:03,920
be different ways of exploring this tech 
tree, and we're still relatively low down. 

580
00:53:03,920 --> 00:53:08,400
We're still at the point where we're just 
understanding these basic fundamental theories,  

581
00:53:08,400 --> 00:53:13,120
and we haven't yet explored them.
A thing which I think is quite fun  

582
00:53:13,120 --> 00:53:17,440
is if you look at the phases of matter.
When I was in school, we'd get taught that  

583
00:53:17,440 --> 00:53:24,960
there are three phases of matter, or sometimes 
four or five, depending on what you included. 

584
00:53:26,480 --> 00:53:33,760
As an adult, as a physicist, you start to 
realize we've been adding to this list. 

585
00:53:33,760 --> 00:53:38,000
We've got superconductors and superfluids, 
and maybe different types of superconductors,  

586
00:53:38,000 --> 00:53:41,760
and Bose-Einstein condensates, 
the quantum Hall systems,  

587
00:53:41,760 --> 00:53:49,280
fractional quantum Hall systems, and so on.
It's starting to turn out there's a lot of  

588
00:53:49,280 --> 00:53:54,400
phases of matter to discover, and we're 
going to discover a lot more of them. 

589
00:53:54,400 --> 00:53:56,880
In fact, we're going to be able to 
start to design them in some sense. 

590
00:53:57,920 --> 00:54:02,800
We'll still be subject to the laws of physics, 
but there is this tremendous freedom in there. 

591
00:54:02,800 --> 00:54:06,640
This looks to me like we're down 
at the bottom of the tech tree. 

592
00:54:06,640 --> 00:54:13,840
We've barely gotten started there, and 
I expect that to be the case broadly. 

593
00:54:13,840 --> 00:54:18,480
Certainly, programming is a 
very natural place to look. 

594
00:54:18,480 --> 00:54:25,040
The idea that we've discovered all the deep ideas 
in programming just seems obviously ludicrous. 

595
00:54:25,680 --> 00:54:34,480
We keep discovering what seem like deep, new, 
fundamental ideas. We're very limited. We're  

596
00:54:34,480 --> 00:54:42,080
basically slightly jumped-up chimpanzees, 
so we're slow and it's taking us time. 

597
00:54:43,600 --> 00:54:51,440
But what do we look like another million 
years in the future, in terms of all the  

598
00:54:51,440 --> 00:54:58,640
different ideas people have had around how 
to manipulate computers and information? 

599
00:54:58,640 --> 00:55:05,920
I think we're likely to discover that there are 
a lot of very deep ideas still to be discovered. 

600
00:55:07,520 --> 00:55:12,960
I think it was Knuth in the preface to The Art of 
Computer Programming who says something like it. 

601
00:55:12,960 --> 00:55:18,320
He started this book back in the sixties.
He talked to a mathematician who was a bit  

602
00:55:18,320 --> 00:55:22,720
contemptuous and said, "Look, computer 
science isn't really a thing yet. 

603
00:55:22,720 --> 00:55:26,480
Come back to me when there's 
a thousand deep theorems." 

604
00:55:26,480 --> 00:55:34,800
Knuth remarks, writing the preface decades later, 
"There clearly are a thousand deep theorems now." 

605
00:55:36,240 --> 00:55:41,040
It's really interesting to think what the 
long-term future is as you get higher and  

606
00:55:41,040 --> 00:55:49,600
higher up in the tech tree, choices about which 
direction we go and how we choose to explore. 

607
00:55:51,040 --> 00:55:56,720
It's potentially the case that different 
civilizations or different choices mean  

608
00:55:56,720 --> 00:56:03,360
we end up in different parts of that tree.
In particular, there are just very basic things  

609
00:56:03,360 --> 00:56:10,640
about how we're very visual creatures, while 
certain other animals are much more aurally based. 

610
00:56:10,640 --> 00:56:15,520
Does that bias the types 
of thoughts that you have? 

611
00:56:15,520 --> 00:56:23,200
Then you extend it to much more exotic kinds 
of civilizations where maybe their biases in  

612
00:56:23,200 --> 00:56:28,960
terms of how they perceive and manipulate 
the world are quite different than ours. 

613
00:56:29,600 --> 00:56:35,280
That might make some significant 
changes in terms of how they do  

614
00:56:35,280 --> 00:56:39,680
that exploration of the tech tree. 
It's all speculation, obviously. 

615
00:56:39,680 --> 00:56:42,000
This is such an interesting take.
I want to better understand it. 

616
00:56:43,920 --> 00:56:47,040
One way to understand it is that 
there might be some things which are  

617
00:56:47,040 --> 00:56:51,120
so fundamental and have such a wide collision 
area against reality that they're inevitably  

618
00:56:51,120 --> 00:56:59,600
going to discover, like general relativity.
Numbers. Numbers. Of all the intelligences in  

619
00:56:59,600 --> 00:57:04,640
the Milky Way galaxy… Maybe that number is one.
Well, actually, arguably we've already  

620
00:57:04,640 --> 00:57:09,200
increased the number.
But of all of those,  

621
00:57:09,200 --> 00:57:17,040
what fraction have the concept of counting? 
It does seem very natural. What fraction have  

622
00:57:17,040 --> 00:57:25,680
discovered the idea of some kind of decimal place 
system? Interesting question. Maybe we're missing  

623
00:57:25,680 --> 00:57:30,000
something really simple and obvious that's 
actually way better than that. What fraction  

624
00:57:30,000 --> 00:57:34,160
got there immediately? What fraction had to 
go through some other intermediate state? 

625
00:57:34,160 --> 00:57:39,280
What fraction uses linear representations 
versus a two-dimensional or a  

626
00:57:39,280 --> 00:57:42,080
three-dimensional representation?
I think the answers to these questions  

627
00:57:42,080 --> 00:57:45,840
are just not at all obvious.
It's a lot of design freedom. 

628
00:57:45,840 --> 00:57:54,960
On theoretical computer science, this is going to 
be extremely naive and arrogant, but I took Scott  

629
00:57:54,960 --> 00:58:01,600
Aaronson's class on complexity theory, and I 
was by far the worst student he's ever had. 

630
00:58:02,160 --> 00:58:08,400
What I remember is there was this period, in 
which you were one of the pioneers, where we  

631
00:58:08,400 --> 00:58:13,760
figured out the class of problems that 
quantum computers can solve and how it  

632
00:58:13,760 --> 00:58:16,960
relates to problems that classical computers 
can solve. It was groundbreaking. It's  

633
00:58:16,960 --> 00:58:22,960
crazy that this works. Since then… There's 
literally this website called Complexity  

634
00:58:22,960 --> 00:58:27,600
Zoo which lists out all the complexity classes.
If you have this complexity class with this kind  

635
00:58:27,600 --> 00:58:33,440
of oracle, it's equivalent to this other class.
It feels like we're building out that taxonomy. 

636
00:58:34,480 --> 00:58:35,760
There are a couple ways to 
understand what you're saying. 

637
00:58:35,760 --> 00:58:39,120
One, maybe you disagree with me that this 
is actually what's happened with this field. 

638
00:58:39,120 --> 00:58:44,720
Another is that while that might happen to 
any one field, who would've thought in 1880  

639
00:58:44,720 --> 00:58:49,040
that computer science, other than Babbage, 
was going to be a thing in the first place? 

640
00:58:49,920 --> 00:58:51,920
We're underestimating how many 
more fields there could be. 

641
00:58:52,880 --> 00:58:56,560
Or maybe you think both, or maybe a 
third secret thing. I'd be curious. 

642
00:58:59,120 --> 00:59:03,680
A very common argument here is 
the low-hanging fruit argument. 

643
00:59:03,680 --> 00:59:06,720
The argument that says there 
should be diminishing returns. 

644
00:59:06,720 --> 00:59:09,200
In fact, empirically we see this.
The amount of scientists in the  

645
00:59:09,200 --> 00:59:16,960
world has exponentially increased.
I think it's worth thinking about why  

646
00:59:16,960 --> 00:59:24,800
you expect diminishing returns and how well 
that argument actually applies in practice. 

647
00:59:24,800 --> 00:59:30,880
An analogy I like is thinking about 
going to an event, like a wedding,  

648
00:59:30,880 --> 00:59:37,200
and you go to the dessert buffet. They've 
put out thirty desserts. Naturally,  

649
00:59:37,200 --> 00:59:43,120
what people do is the best desserts go first.
We don't quite have a well-ordered preference  

650
00:59:43,120 --> 00:59:47,200
there, so maybe there's some difference, 
but human beings are fairly similar,  

651
00:59:47,200 --> 00:59:53,440
so the best desserts will go first.
This is an argument for why you expect  

652
00:59:53,440 --> 00:59:58,720
diminishing returns in a lot of different fields.
If it's relatively easy to see what's available  

653
00:59:58,720 --> 01:00:03,200
and people have similar preferences, 
then the best stuff goes first and it  

654
01:00:03,200 --> 01:00:10,800
just gets worse and worse after that.
If you look at a very static snapshot  

655
01:00:10,800 --> 01:00:15,840
in time of scientific progress, 
maybe there's some truth to that. 

656
01:00:16,640 --> 01:00:21,440
But if somebody is standing behind the dessert 
table and is replenishing and restocking the  

657
01:00:21,440 --> 01:00:27,280
desserts and keeps adding new ones in, 
it may turn out that a little bit later,  

658
01:00:27,280 --> 01:00:33,520
much better desserts appear, and you're 
going to go and eat those instead. 

659
01:00:33,520 --> 01:00:35,680
Scientific progress has a 
little bit of that flavor. 

660
01:00:36,640 --> 01:00:40,560
We go through these funny time periods.
Computer science is a great example,  

661
01:00:40,560 --> 01:00:48,720
where computer science basically arose as a 
side effect of some pretty abstruse questions  

662
01:00:48,720 --> 01:00:57,760
in the philosophy of mathematics and logic.
You've got these people trying to attack  

663
01:00:57,760 --> 01:01:03,120
these rather esoteric questions that 
seem quite high up in exploration,  

664
01:01:04,240 --> 01:01:08,640
and they discover this fundamental new field, 
and all of a sudden there's an explosion there. 

665
01:01:09,760 --> 01:01:12,480
The diminishing returns argument 
just didn't apply there. 

666
01:01:12,480 --> 01:01:19,360
We just weren't able to see what was there.
This has been the case over and over again. 

667
01:01:19,360 --> 01:01:24,400
New fields arrive and all of a sudden, and 
boom, it's easy to make progress again. 

668
01:01:24,400 --> 01:01:28,880
Young people flood in because you can be 
twenty-one and make major breakthroughs  

669
01:01:28,880 --> 01:01:32,000
rather than having to spend twenty-five 
years mastering everything that's been  

670
01:01:32,000 --> 01:01:40,000
done before. It's obviously very attractive. 
I'm not sure anybody understands very well  

671
01:01:40,960 --> 01:01:47,040
the dynamics of that, or how to think about 
why the structure of knowledge is that way,  

672
01:01:47,040 --> 01:01:54,640
where these new fields keep opening up.
But it does seem empirically to be the case. 

673
01:01:54,640 --> 01:01:58,880
Despite the fact that that is 
the case… Take deep learning. 

674
01:01:58,880 --> 01:02:04,960
Obviously, this is an example of a new field 
where twenty-one-year-olds can make progress and  

675
01:02:05,760 --> 01:02:08,960
it's relatively new.
Fifteen years or so  

676
01:02:08,960 --> 01:02:16,400
since it got back into high gear.
But already we're in a stage where  

677
01:02:16,400 --> 01:02:20,000
you need billions, tens of billions, 
or hundreds of billions of dollars  

678
01:02:20,000 --> 01:02:24,640
to keep making progress at the frontier.
There are a couple ways to understand that. 

679
01:02:24,640 --> 01:02:28,640
One is that it actually is harder than the 
kinds of things the ancients had to do,  

680
01:02:28,640 --> 01:02:33,520
or is more intensive at least.
Second is it might not have been,  

681
01:02:33,520 --> 01:02:37,360
but because our civilizational resources are 
so large, the amount of people is so large,  

682
01:02:37,360 --> 01:02:41,600
the amount of money is so large, we can basically 
make the kind of progress it would have taken  

683
01:02:41,600 --> 01:02:47,440
the ancients forever to make almost immediately.
We notice something is productive and immediately  

684
01:02:47,440 --> 01:02:51,520
dump in all the resources.
But it's also weird that  

685
01:02:51,520 --> 01:02:55,440
there's not that many of them.
I feel like deep learning is notable  

686
01:02:55,440 --> 01:02:59,040
because it is one big exception to the fact 
that it's hard to think of other examples. 

687
01:02:59,040 --> 01:03:03,120
I think that's a consequence of 
the architecture of attention. 

688
01:03:03,760 --> 01:03:08,400
At any given time, there's 
always a most successful thing. 

689
01:03:09,200 --> 01:03:12,000
If deep learning wasn't a thing, 
maybe you'd be talking about CRISPR. 

690
01:03:12,000 --> 01:03:23,120
Maybe we wouldn't think about solving the protein 
structure prediction problem as a success of AI. 

691
01:03:23,120 --> 01:03:28,240
Maybe we would have figured out how to do it 
with curve fitting, more broadly construed,  

692
01:03:28,240 --> 01:03:31,280
and we'd just be like, "Wow, that 
took a lot of computing resources." 

693
01:03:31,280 --> 01:03:36,720
But protein structure prediction might 
be an enormously important thing. 

694
01:03:36,720 --> 01:03:43,920
There is always our biggest thing.
What you're pointing at is more a consequence  

695
01:03:43,920 --> 01:03:49,840
of the way in which attention gets centralized.
It's basically fashion, is what I'm saying. 

696
01:03:49,840 --> 01:03:53,520
It's not just fashion, but 
there is some dynamic there. 

697
01:03:54,240 --> 01:03:58,400
There's a very interesting and 
important implication of this idea. 

698
01:03:59,040 --> 01:04:05,440
That the branching is so wide and so 
contingent and so path-dependent that  

699
01:04:05,440 --> 01:04:08,720
different civilizations would stumble 
on entirely different technology stacks. 

700
01:04:08,720 --> 01:04:13,040
There's a very interesting implication that 
there will be gains from trade into the far,  

701
01:04:13,040 --> 01:04:17,600
far future, which might actually be one of the 
most important facts about the far future in  

702
01:04:17,600 --> 01:04:21,920
terms of how civilizations are set up, how 
they coordinate, and how they interface. 

703
01:04:22,800 --> 01:04:28,640
There's not this "go forth and exploit."
There are humongous gains to trade from  

704
01:04:28,640 --> 01:04:35,120
adjacent colonies or whatever.
Sort of. There's a question of  

705
01:04:35,120 --> 01:04:40,160
what's actually hard.
If it's just the ideas,  

706
01:04:40,160 --> 01:04:44,400
well, those spread relatively quickly.
It's relatively easy to share ideas. 

707
01:04:44,400 --> 01:04:48,080
If it's something more, it's 
almost a Dan Wang kind of idea  

708
01:04:48,080 --> 01:04:53,840
where there's some notion of capacity.
You need all the right techs, you need all  

709
01:04:53,840 --> 01:04:59,760
the right manufacturing capacity, and so on.
So civilization A has a very different kind  

710
01:04:59,760 --> 01:05:03,760
of manufacturing capacity, and it's just 
not so easy to build in civilization B. 

711
01:05:03,760 --> 01:05:08,240
Even if civilization B is ahead, 
I think that becomes true. 

712
01:05:08,240 --> 01:05:16,720
There is a comparative advantage which 
is going to provide massive benefits  

713
01:05:16,720 --> 01:05:19,520
to trade in both directions.
Eventually, you expect some  

714
01:05:19,520 --> 01:05:23,440
diffusion of innovation.
It is funny to think about  

715
01:05:23,440 --> 01:05:26,880
what the barriers are there.
A fun thought experiment I like  

716
01:05:26,880 --> 01:05:34,960
to think about is GitHub but for aliens.
Somebody presents you with all of the code  

717
01:05:36,400 --> 01:05:40,160
from some alien civilization.
I don't even know what code means  

718
01:05:40,160 --> 01:05:50,080
there, but their specification of algorithms.
It would have many interesting new ideas in there,  

719
01:05:50,080 --> 01:05:56,160
and it would take forever for human beings to 
dig through and try and extract all of those. 

720
01:05:56,160 --> 01:06:04,320
The origin of this for me was 
thinking about proteins in nature. 

721
01:06:05,120 --> 01:06:12,480
We've been gifted this incredible variety of 
machines which we don't really understand at all. 

722
01:06:12,480 --> 01:06:17,200
We just have to go and try and 
understand them on a one-by-one basis. 

723
01:06:17,200 --> 01:06:20,880
We're still understanding hemoglobin 
and insulin and things like this. 

724
01:06:23,120 --> 01:06:28,000
There are hundreds of millions of proteins known.
So it is a little bit like that. 

725
01:06:28,000 --> 01:06:36,400
We've been gifted by biology this immense library 
of machines, no doubt containing an enormous  

726
01:06:36,400 --> 01:06:41,760
number of very interesting ideas, and we're just 
at the very, very beginning of understanding it. 

727
01:06:43,360 --> 01:06:51,040
I suppose your point—I need to relabel 
your argument slightly—but you think of  

728
01:06:51,040 --> 01:06:56,560
that as a gift from an alien civilization, which 
obviously it isn't, but you think of it that way. 

729
01:06:56,560 --> 01:07:02,640
And oh my goodness, there's so much 
in there and we're going to study it. 

730
01:07:02,640 --> 01:07:04,960
Goodness knows how long we 
could continue to study it. 

731
01:07:04,960 --> 01:07:09,200
There are tens of thousands of papers 
about hemoglobin and things like that,  

732
01:07:09,200 --> 01:07:13,760
and we still don't understand them, and yet 
we're getting so much out of it. Just think about  

733
01:07:13,760 --> 01:07:23,120
insulin alone. It's such an important thing.
That's an incredibly useful intuition pump,  

734
01:07:23,120 --> 01:07:27,680
that you have on Earth… I had Nick Lane on 
where he had this theory about how life emerged,  

735
01:07:27,680 --> 01:07:34,240
but whatever theory you have, something 
like DNA has had four billion years. 

736
01:07:34,240 --> 01:07:37,440
You have an alien civilization come here 
and be like, "There's all these interesting  

737
01:07:37,440 --> 01:07:47,520
things to learn about material science."
Think about kinesin walking along. We know  

738
01:07:47,520 --> 01:07:52,320
almost nothing about these proteins, and yet the 
tiny few facts we do know are just incredible. 

739
01:07:52,320 --> 01:08:01,840
The ribosome is another example, this 
miraculous sort of device, a little factory. 

740
01:08:01,840 --> 01:08:09,760
All seeded by this particular chemistry on Earth 
with nucleic acids and carbon-based life forms. 

741
01:08:09,760 --> 01:08:13,200
That chemistry gives rise to all of 
these interesting things which an  

742
01:08:13,200 --> 01:08:19,680
alien civilization would find very interesting.
That very seed, which must be one among trillions  

743
01:08:19,680 --> 01:08:25,920
of possible seeds of general intellectual 
ideas, leads to all this fecundity. 

744
01:08:25,920 --> 01:08:29,440
That's a very interesting intuition pump.
I want to meditate on this "gains from trade"  

745
01:08:29,440 --> 01:08:34,640
thing because I feel like there's something very 
interesting about this idea that if you have this  

746
01:08:34,640 --> 01:08:39,280
vision of how technology progresses and how it 
may be different in different civilizations,  

747
01:08:39,280 --> 01:08:42,080
it actually has important implications 
about how different civilizations  

748
01:08:42,080 --> 01:08:45,200
might interact with each other.
The fact that there are going  

749
01:08:45,200 --> 01:08:48,560
to be these huge gains from trade.
It makes friendliness much more rewarding? 

750
01:08:48,560 --> 01:08:54,400
Yes. That's a very important observation.
I hadn't thought about that at all. 

751
01:08:54,400 --> 01:09:02,000
That is a very interesting observation. It 
is funny. Comparative advantage is something  

752
01:09:02,000 --> 01:09:10,640
that people love to invoke and it's a very 
beautiful idea obviously. There are limits to it.  

753
01:09:16,720 --> 01:09:23,680
It's a special limited model. Chimpanzees can do 
interesting things, but we don't trade with them. 

754
01:09:26,560 --> 01:09:29,840
I think it's interesting to 
think about the reasons why. 

755
01:09:31,120 --> 01:09:36,320
Part of it is just power, I think.
Once there's a sufficiently large power imbalance,  

756
01:09:38,160 --> 01:09:44,400
very often—not always, but very often—groups 
of people seem to shift into this other  

757
01:09:44,400 --> 01:09:49,280
mode where they just seek to dominate.
Maybe there's something special about human  

758
01:09:49,280 --> 01:09:57,680
beings, but maybe it's also a more general thing.
You need all these special things to be  

759
01:09:57,680 --> 01:10:05,520
true before groups will trade. 
It's not necessarily obvious. 

760
01:10:05,520 --> 01:10:08,880
I think the big thing going on 
here is one, transaction costs. 

761
01:10:09,760 --> 01:10:17,920
Two, comparative advantage does not tell you 
that the terms on which the trade happens  

762
01:10:17,920 --> 01:10:22,880
are above subsistence for any given producer.
People often bring this up in the context of,  

763
01:10:22,880 --> 01:10:26,720
"Well, humans will be employed even in a 
post-AGI world because of comparative advantage." 

764
01:10:26,720 --> 01:10:32,400
There are five different ways that argument breaks 
down, but the easiest way to understand it is:  

765
01:10:32,400 --> 01:10:36,560
why don't we have horses all around on the roads?
Because there's some comparative advantage  

766
01:10:36,560 --> 01:10:40,880
between cars and horses.
One, there are huge  

767
01:10:40,880 --> 01:10:45,680
transaction costs to building roads that are 
compatible with horses and cars at the same time. 

768
01:10:45,680 --> 01:10:52,080
In a similar way, AI thinking at 1,000 times the 
speed that can shoot their latent states at each  

769
01:10:52,080 --> 01:10:57,680
other is going to find it way more costly 
than the benefit, in terms of interacting  

770
01:10:57,680 --> 01:11:07,120
with a human being in the supply chain.
Second, just because horses have a comparative  

771
01:11:07,120 --> 01:11:14,160
advantage mathematically does not mean that it 
is worth paying $100,000 a year, or whatever  

772
01:11:14,160 --> 01:11:19,600
it costs to sustain a horse in San Francisco.
That subsistence isn't going to be worth the  

773
01:11:19,600 --> 01:11:22,240
benefit you get out of the horse.
I do think it's interesting,  

774
01:11:23,280 --> 01:11:31,120
the sheer fact… My expectation and my intuition 
obviously differs a great deal from yours on this. 

775
01:11:32,080 --> 01:11:35,440
Most parts of the tech tree 
are never going to be explored. 

776
01:11:35,440 --> 01:11:38,240
There are just too many interesting 
ways of combining things. 

777
01:11:38,240 --> 01:11:45,600
There are too many deep ideas waiting to be 
discovered, and not only we, but nobody ever  

778
01:11:45,600 --> 01:11:50,160
