01:29:36,400 --> 01:29:39,360
What similar story could you 
have told 10 years earlier? 

970
01:29:41,840 --> 01:29:47,120
The conditions don't exist for it.
I mean, it's quite a banal story, but… 

971
01:29:47,120 --> 01:29:53,280
One of the things we were going to discuss was 
this idea you had about the market for follow-ups. 

972
01:29:53,280 --> 01:29:58,160
I think this is the perfect story to 
discuss it for because you wrote the  

973
01:29:58,160 --> 01:30:04,800
textbook about the field. "Mike and Ike" is 
the definitive textbook on quantum information. 

974
01:30:06,560 --> 01:30:12,480
You presumably came in after Deutsch.
But you in the '90s somehow identified  

975
01:30:12,480 --> 01:30:17,520
it as the thing that is worth 
following up on and building on. 

976
01:30:17,520 --> 01:30:20,480
Instead of talking about it more abstractly, 
I'd love to just hear the firsthand story  

977
01:30:20,480 --> 01:30:25,360
of how you knew that this is the thing to do.
Of all the things that were happening in physics  

978
01:30:25,360 --> 01:30:28,240
and computing, how did you decide 
you want to think about this problem? 

979
01:30:30,720 --> 01:30:35,600
Richard Feynman writes this great paper in 1982.
David Deutsch writes an absolutely fantastic  

980
01:30:35,600 --> 01:30:44,720
paper in 1985 sketching out a lot of the 
fundamental ideas of quantum computing. I'm  

981
01:30:44,720 --> 01:30:49,600
11 in 1985. I'm not thinking about this. 
I'm playing soccer and doing whatever. 

982
01:30:49,600 --> 01:30:55,920
But in 1992, I took a class on quantum mechanics 
that was really terrific, given by Gerard Milburn. 

983
01:30:56,800 --> 01:31:02,320
I just went and asked Gerard one day 
after the fifth lecture or something. 

984
01:31:02,320 --> 01:31:09,520
I said, "Do you have any papers or 
whatever that you could give me?" 

985
01:31:09,520 --> 01:31:12,320
He said, "Come by my office 
in a couple of days' time." 

986
01:31:12,320 --> 01:31:19,120
I did, and he presented me with a giant stack 
of papers, which included the Deutsch paper,  

987
01:31:19,120 --> 01:31:24,720
the Feynman paper, and a whole bunch of other 
very fundamental papers about quantum computing  

988
01:31:24,720 --> 01:31:32,960
and quantum information at a time when essentially 
nobody in the world was working on it. He was. I  

989
01:31:32,960 --> 01:31:39,880
think he wrote the very first paper that proposed 
a practical approach to quantum computing. 

990
01:31:39,880 --> 01:31:44,080
It wasn't very practical, but it 
was actually in a real system. 

991
01:31:44,080 --> 01:31:51,840
So in some sense, I'm benefiting 
from the taste of this other person. 

992
01:31:51,840 --> 01:31:56,480
As soon as I read the papers… 
These are exciting papers. 

993
01:31:57,040 --> 01:32:03,120
They're asking very fundamental questions, 
and you realize I can make progress here. 

994
01:32:03,680 --> 01:32:05,760
These are things that one 
could potentially work on. 

995
01:32:06,480 --> 01:32:22,320
Deutsch has this conjecture, or thesis or whatever 
you’d call it, that a universal model, a quantum  

996
01:32:22,320 --> 01:32:28,560
Turing machine, should be capable of efficiently 
simulating any physical system at all. 

997
01:32:28,560 --> 01:32:32,960
This is a very provocative idea.
I think in that paper,  

998
01:32:32,960 --> 01:32:39,680
he more or less claims that he's proved it.
I'm not sure everybody would agree with that. 

999
01:32:39,680 --> 01:32:44,880
There are questions about whether or not you 
can simulate quantum field theory effectively. 

1000
01:32:45,760 --> 01:32:50,320
That kind of question is very 
interesting and very exciting. 

1001
01:32:52,160 --> 01:32:55,600
It's obviously a fundamental 
question about the universe. 

1002
01:32:56,240 --> 01:33:04,400
He has some wonderful ideas in there about 
quantum algorithms, where they come from,  

1003
01:33:04,400 --> 01:33:07,920
what they mean, and what they relate 
to the meaning of the wave function. 

1004
01:33:07,920 --> 01:33:15,200
Questions like this are still not 
agreed upon amongst physicists. 

1005
01:33:16,080 --> 01:33:20,320
There's just some sense of, "Oh, I am in contact 
with something which is (A) deeply important,  

1006
01:33:20,320 --> 01:33:26,160
and (B) we as a civilization don't have this."
Of course, you start to focus  

1007
01:33:26,160 --> 01:33:34,320
your attention a little bit there.
I'm not sure I got the answer to the question… 

1008
01:33:35,440 --> 01:33:42,160
Maybe I misunderstood the question.
Maybe I'll explain the motivation first. 

1009
01:33:44,080 --> 01:33:48,960
In a previous conversation, we were discussing how 
you could have known in the 1940s that the Shannon  

1010
01:33:48,960 --> 01:33:57,840
theorems and Shannon's way of thinking about a 
communication channel is a deep idea that goes  

1011
01:33:57,840 --> 01:34:02,080
beyond the problems with pulse-code modulation 
that Bell Labs was trying to solve at the time,  

1012
01:34:02,080 --> 01:34:08,480
and that it applies to everything from quantum 
mechanics to genetics to computer science. 

1013
01:34:09,840 --> 01:34:15,280
One of the ideas you stated that we 
didn't get a chance to talk about  

1014
01:34:15,280 --> 01:34:19,520
yet… Shannon published this paper.
There are all these other papers,  

1015
01:34:19,520 --> 01:34:23,760
but there's some market of follow-ups where 
people gravitate to and build upon Shannon's work. 

1016
01:34:23,760 --> 01:34:26,720
How do they realize that that's the thing 
to do, and how does that process happen? 

1017
01:34:29,760 --> 01:34:33,200
I guess you gave your local answer.
You read these papers, and you  

1018
01:34:33,200 --> 01:34:37,680
immediately realized there's work to be 
done here. There's low-hanging fruit.  

1019
01:34:37,680 --> 01:34:40,640
There's some deep provocative idea 
that I need to better understand,  

1020
01:34:40,640 --> 01:34:48,000
and I could tractably make progress on.
To some extent, you're saying, "Okay,  

1021
01:34:48,000 --> 01:34:57,280
I wanted to get into this game of contributing to 
humanity's understanding of the universe," and you  

1022
01:34:57,280 --> 01:35:01,840
are applying this low-hanging fruit algorithm.
You're like, "elative to my particular set of  

1023
01:35:01,840 --> 01:35:07,440
interests and abilities, where should 
I pick up my shovel and start digging?" 

1024
01:35:08,800 --> 01:35:14,160
There it was like, "Oh, this looks like 
quite a good place to start digging." 

1025
01:35:16,880 --> 01:35:20,160
Different people, of course, 
chose very differently. 

1026
01:35:21,040 --> 01:35:28,480
It was a very unusual choice at the time. This was 
1992. Very few people were thinking about that. 

1027
01:35:29,120 --> 01:35:34,240
Fast-forwarding a bit, I don't know how 
you think about your work on the open  

1028
01:35:34,240 --> 01:35:40,640
science movement now, but did it work?
What does success there look like? 

1029
01:35:41,200 --> 01:35:51,360
What is the movement trying to accomplish?
It's interesting. You didn't stop and define  

1030
01:35:51,360 --> 01:35:58,960
open science there, which 20 years ago you would 
have had to do. People recognize the phrase.  

1031
01:35:58,960 --> 01:36:03,600
People have some set of associations with it.
Most often, they have a relatively simple  

1032
01:36:03,600 --> 01:36:06,000
set of associations.
It means maybe something  

1033
01:36:06,000 --> 01:36:11,040
about making scientific papers open access.
Very often they have some set of notions about  

1034
01:36:11,600 --> 01:36:17,360
also making code openly available 
or making data openly available. 

1035
01:36:19,920 --> 01:36:27,680
Those are already very large successes of the open 
science movement, to make those salient issues. 

1036
01:36:27,680 --> 01:36:33,760
Those are issues on which people have opinions, 
and there are relatively common arguments. 

1037
01:36:35,200 --> 01:36:40,240
This is like the meme version: publicly 
funded science should be open science. 

1038
01:36:42,160 --> 01:36:47,600
That's a distillation of a set of ideas 
which you might be able to contest. 

1039
01:36:47,600 --> 01:36:52,640
But if you can get people actually thinking 
about it and engaged with that kind of argument,  

1040
01:36:53,520 --> 01:37:01,680
that's a very fundamental issue to be considering 
in the whole political economy of science. 

1041
01:37:01,680 --> 01:37:09,280
If you go back three centuries, there 
was a very similar argument prosecuted,  

1042
01:37:09,280 --> 01:37:13,040
which is the question: do we publicly 
disclose our scientific results or not? 

1043
01:37:13,040 --> 01:37:19,360
If you look at people like Galileo and 
Kepler, the extent to which they publicly  

1044
01:37:19,360 --> 01:37:26,240
disclosed was done in a very odd way.
Sometimes they did bizarre things where  

1045
01:37:26,240 --> 01:37:38,160
they published some of their results as anagrams.
They'd find some discovery, write down the result  

1046
01:37:38,160 --> 01:38:02,560
in a sentence, scramble it, and publish that.
Then if somebody else later made the same  

1047
01:38:02,560 --> 01:38:07,040
discovery, they would unscramble the anagram 
and say, "Oh, yeah, I actually did it first." 

1048
01:38:07,040 --> 01:38:12,720
This is not an ideal foundation 
for a discovery system. 

1049
01:38:12,720 --> 01:38:20,240
It took a very long time, over a century, I think, 
to obtain more or less the modern ideals, in which  

1050
01:38:20,880 --> 01:38:27,840
you disclose the knowledge in the form of a paper.
There is an expectation of attribution, and a  

1051
01:38:27,840 --> 01:38:34,240
reputation economy gets built. "So-and-so did this 
work, so they deserve the credit for that," and  

1052
01:38:34,240 --> 01:38:37,200
that's the basis for their careers.
This is the underlying  

1053
01:38:37,200 --> 01:38:42,640
political economy of science.
That made a lot of sense when you have a printing  

1054
01:38:42,640 --> 01:38:48,160
press and the ability to do scientific journals.
Then you transition to this modern situation,  

1055
01:38:48,160 --> 01:38:51,840
where you can start to share a lot more.
You can share your code,  

1056
01:38:52,560 --> 01:39:00,960
your data, your in-progress ideas.
But there's no direct credit associated to those. 

1057
01:39:00,960 --> 01:39:10,240
It's not at all obvious how much reputation 
should be associated to them. That's all  

1058
01:39:10,240 --> 01:39:17,440
constructed socially. Making it a live issue 
is a very important thing to have done. 

1059
01:39:18,080 --> 01:39:23,520
I view that as one of the main positive 
outcomes of work on open science. 

1060
01:39:23,520 --> 01:39:27,840
I'll give you a really practical 
example to illustrate the problem. 

1061
01:39:28,800 --> 01:39:35,440
For a long time in physics, there was a preprint 
culture in which people would upload preprints  

1062
01:39:37,040 --> 01:39:42,400
to the preprint archive, and 
in biology, this didn't happen.  

1063
01:39:42,400 --> 01:39:47,200
There was no preprint culture. That's changing 
now, but for a long time, this was the case. 

1064
01:39:47,200 --> 01:39:53,440
I used to amuse myself by asking physicists 
and biologists why this was the case. 

1065
01:39:54,080 --> 01:40:01,680
What I would hear from biologists was they would 
say, "Biology is so much more competitive than  

1066
01:40:01,680 --> 01:40:09,360
physics that we need to protect our priority, 
so we can't possibly upload to the archive. 

1067
01:40:10,080 --> 01:40:14,480
We have to just publish in journals."
Then I would sometimes hear from physicists,  

1068
01:40:14,480 --> 01:40:18,080
"Physics is so much more competitive 
than biology that we need to establish  

1069
01:40:18,080 --> 01:40:22,720
our priority by uploading as rapidly 
as possible to the preprint archive. 

1070
01:40:22,720 --> 01:40:25,280
We can't possibly wait to 
do it with the journals." 

1071
01:40:25,280 --> 01:40:28,960
I think this emphasizes the extent to 
which this kind of attribution economy  

1072
01:40:28,960 --> 01:40:34,080
is just something we construct.
It's something we do by agreement. 

1073
01:40:36,000 --> 01:40:42,080
Any attempt to change that economy results in a 
different system by which we construct knowledge. 

1074
01:40:43,600 --> 01:40:49,120
There is this very fundamental set of problems 
around the political economy of science. 

1075
01:40:51,600 --> 01:40:55,520
We've got this collective project, 
and how we mediate it depends upon  

1076
01:40:56,640 --> 01:41:01,760
the economy we have around ideas.
One of the things you've emphasized  

1077
01:41:01,760 --> 01:41:06,400
as a part of this project of open science, and we 
talked about it earlier, is collective science,  

1078
01:41:06,400 --> 01:41:11,120
or groups of people making progress on a 
problem where no individual understands  

1079
01:41:11,120 --> 01:41:20,080
all the logical and explanatory levels 
necessary to make a leap or a connection. 

1080
01:41:20,080 --> 01:41:24,320
Outside of mathematics, what is the 
best example of such a discovery? 

1081
01:41:24,320 --> 01:41:28,000
I'm not sure I have a well-ordering 
of them to give you a best. 

1082
01:41:29,600 --> 01:41:34,800
An example that I think is very 
interesting is the LHC, where it's  

1083
01:41:34,800 --> 01:41:42,160
just this immensely complicated object.
Years ago, I snuck into an accelerator  

1084
01:41:42,160 --> 01:41:44,240
physics conference.
I didn't know anything at  

1085
01:41:44,240 --> 01:41:49,120
all about accelerator physics, but I was just 
curious to see what they were talking about. 

1086
01:41:49,120 --> 01:41:53,680
This particular group of people 
were experts on numerical methods,  

1087
01:41:53,680 --> 01:41:59,200
in particular on inverse methods.
Inside these accelerators,  

1088
01:41:59,200 --> 01:42:04,880
you have these cascades.
A particle will be massively accelerated, maybe  

1089
01:42:04,880 --> 01:42:10,560
it'll be collided, and then you'll get a shower 
of particles which decays and decays and decays. 

1090
01:42:10,560 --> 01:42:17,360
There's just this incredible, consequential 
shower, which is ultimately what you see  

1091
01:42:17,360 --> 01:42:20,080
at the detector.
Then you have to  

1092
01:42:20,080 --> 01:42:25,920
retroactively figure out what produced it.
There are these very complicated inverse  

1093
01:42:25,920 --> 01:42:29,280
problems that need to be solved.
You've got this final data,  

1094
01:42:29,280 --> 01:42:33,520
but you need to figure out what produced it, 
and that's how you look for signatures of these. 

1095
01:42:34,080 --> 01:42:40,160
Many of these people were incredibly 
deep experts on simulation methods  

1096
01:42:40,160 --> 01:42:46,800
for following particle tracks.
This was really deep and difficult stuff. 

1097
01:42:46,800 --> 01:42:52,480
I was like, "Wow, you could spend a lifetime 
just learning how to do this and how to solve  

1098
01:42:52,480 --> 01:43:00,240
some of these inverse problems, and you would know 
very little about quantum field theory, detector  

1099
01:43:00,240 --> 01:43:09,600
physics, vacuum physics, or data processing, 
all these things that are absolutely essential  

1100
01:43:09,600 --> 01:43:17,440
to understanding, say, the Higgs boson".
I don't think it's possible for one person  

1101
01:43:17,440 --> 01:43:22,960
to understand everything in depth.
Lots of people broadly understand a  

1102
01:43:22,960 --> 01:43:29,280
lot of these ideas, but they don't understand 
everything in the depth that is actually utilized. 

1103
01:43:29,280 --> 01:43:34,080
That's why there are these papers 
with well over a thousand authors. 

1104
01:43:34,880 --> 01:43:39,040
Those people can talk to one another at a 
high level, but they don't understand each  

1105
01:43:39,040 --> 01:43:44,640
other's specialties in all that much depth.
Things like detector physics, vacuum physics,  

1106
01:43:45,440 --> 01:43:50,480
solving inverse problems, this stuff is 
incredibly different from each other. 

1107
01:43:52,480 --> 01:44:01,120
To understand it in real detail is serious work.
How do you think about prolificness versus depth? 

1108
01:44:02,080 --> 01:44:07,920
Maybe Darwin's an example of somebody who's 
just gestating on something for many decades.  

1109
01:44:07,920 --> 01:44:11,280
There are other examples. Einstein during the 
year he comes up with special relativity is  

1110
01:44:11,280 --> 01:44:14,640
just doing a bunch of different things.
And Pais talks about how they were all  

1111
01:44:14,640 --> 01:44:20,560
relevant to the eventual build-up.
It's something I stress about a lot. 

1112
01:44:20,560 --> 01:44:24,880
Sometimes I feel I'm too slow.
It's funny though, the Darwin  

1113
01:44:24,880 --> 01:44:33,040
example is really interesting. Prolific at 
what? God knows how many letters he wrote. 

1114
01:44:33,040 --> 01:44:39,120
It must have been an enormous number.
So he was certainly very active. 

1115
01:44:41,920 --> 01:44:46,560
There's two types of work that tend to be 
involved in any kind of creative project. 

1116
01:44:46,560 --> 01:44:49,920
There's routine stuff, and there you 
just want to avoid procrastination. 

1117
01:44:49,920 --> 01:44:54,320
You just want to ask, "How do I get good at this?" 
or "How do I outsource it?" and "How do I do it as  

1118
01:44:54,320 --> 01:45:01,920
rapidly as possible?" and just avoid getting 
into a situation where you're prolonging it. 

1119
01:45:02,800 --> 01:45:11,200
Then there's high-variance stuff where you 
actually need to be willing to take a lot of time. 

1120
01:45:11,200 --> 01:45:15,120
You need to be willing to go to different 
places and talk to different people,  

1121
01:45:15,120 --> 01:45:19,840
where in any given instance, most of 
it is just not going to be an input. 

1122
01:45:20,720 --> 01:45:25,280
Somehow balancing those two things… I 
think a lot of people are very good at  

1123
01:45:25,280 --> 01:45:31,920
doing one or the other, but it's almost like 
a personality trait which one you prefer. 

1124
01:45:31,920 --> 01:45:37,440
People tend to end up doing a lot 
of one and not enough of the other. 

1125
01:45:37,440 --> 01:45:45,040
So I certainly try and balance those two things.
Einstein is such an interesting example. 1905  

1126
01:45:45,040 --> 01:45:48,800
is just this extraordinary year.
You can delete special relativity  

1127
01:45:48,800 --> 01:45:53,360
entirely, and it's an extraordinary year.
You can delete special relativity, and you can  

1128
01:45:53,360 --> 01:45:58,320
delete the photoelectric effect for which he won 
the Nobel Prize, and it's still an extraordinary  

1129
01:45:58,320 --> 01:46:07,520
year, plausibly a multi-Nobel-Prize-winning 
year. So what's he doing? Maybe the answer is  

1130
01:46:07,520 --> 01:46:12,640
just that he's smarter than the rest of us.
There's a lot of luck as well. 

1131
01:46:16,960 --> 01:46:22,560
Certainly for myself anyway, trying to 
identify those things that are routine  

1132
01:46:22,560 --> 01:46:27,600
that I should get good at, and then just 
try to do them as quickly as possible. 

1133
01:46:27,600 --> 01:46:30,400
I think that's yielded a 
certain amount of returns. 

1134
01:46:30,400 --> 01:46:34,560
But also being willing to bet a 
little bit more on myself on the  

1135
01:46:34,560 --> 01:46:41,680
variance side has also been very, very helpful.
That's really hard, because intrinsically you're  

1136
01:46:41,680 --> 01:46:45,280
putting yourself in situations where you 
don't know what the outcome is going to be. 

1137
01:46:45,920 --> 01:46:52,320
If you're very driven to be productive, and 
actually mostly it's not working over there,  

1138
01:46:52,320 --> 01:46:57,440
you think, "Let's reduce this." It doesn't 
feel right. When I worked in San Francisco,  

1139
01:46:58,000 --> 01:47:04,320
a practice I used to have each day was 
instead of taking the 15-minute walk to work,  

1140
01:47:04,320 --> 01:47:08,000
I would take the more beautiful 30-minute walk. 

1141
01:47:08,000 --> 01:47:14,240
Partially just because it was beautiful, but 
partially also as just a reminder that there  

1142
01:47:14,240 --> 01:47:19,200
are real benefits to not being efficient.
But it's not an answer to your question. 

1143
01:47:19,200 --> 01:47:22,400
Really, I think all I'm saying is 
I struggle a lot with the question. 

1144
01:47:22,400 --> 01:47:30,320
I think Dean Keith Simonton has this 
famous equal odds rule where he says  

1145
01:47:30,320 --> 01:47:34,880
the probability that any given thing you 
release—any paper, book, whatever—will  

1146
01:47:34,880 --> 01:47:40,480
be extremely important for a given person 
through their lifetime is not that different. 

1147
01:47:40,480 --> 01:47:48,240
What really determines in what era they are the 
most productive is how much they're publishing. 

1148
01:47:48,240 --> 01:47:52,640
Any given thing has equal odds 
of being extremely important. 

1149
01:47:53,360 --> 01:47:58,240
I think some of the most successful creatives 
or scientists, they're just doing a lot. 

1150
01:47:58,240 --> 01:48:03,200
Shakespeare was just publishing a lot.
Of course, then there are counterexamples. Gödel  

1151
01:48:03,200 --> 01:48:17,040
published almost nothing. But broadly speaking, 
you need a very good reason to not do that. 

1152
01:48:17,040 --> 01:48:23,680
It's funny, I've met a lot of people 
over the years who are clearly brilliant,  

1153
01:48:23,680 --> 01:48:28,080
and they're just obsessed that they are going to 
work on the great project that makes them famous,  

1154
01:48:28,080 --> 01:48:33,680
and they never do anything. That seems connected. 
It's a type of aversiveness. I think very  

1155
01:48:33,680 --> 01:48:39,120
often they just don't want public judgment.
Something that I would love to see… There's  

1156
01:48:39,120 --> 01:48:45,760
an awful lot of biographies and memoirs 
and histories of people who achieve a lot. 

1157
01:48:45,760 --> 01:48:50,160
I wish there was a very large 
number of biographies of people  

1158
01:48:50,160 --> 01:49:02,960
who are fantastically talented who just missed.
I've known people who won gold medals at IMOs  

1159
01:49:02,960 --> 01:49:11,040
and things like that, who then tried to become 
