1193
01:52:27,200 --> 01:52:31,040
If I understand that, I have 
some good understanding. 

1194
01:52:31,040 --> 01:52:34,880
The problem is with almost every other 
field, there's not this curriculum. 

1195
01:52:37,120 --> 01:52:41,440
When I interviewed Ilya three, four years 
ago, it was: implement the transformer,  

1196
01:52:41,440 --> 01:52:45,280
and if you implement it, you have some nugget 
of understanding you have clamped down. 

1197
01:52:45,280 --> 01:52:52,000
With other fields, it's just that I vaguely 
understand this. It's not clamped. There's  

1198
01:52:52,000 --> 01:52:58,000
no forcing function of "do this exercise, 
and if you do it, you will understand." 

1199
01:52:58,560 --> 01:53:04,080
Really what you're saying is you can do 
a good job at podcasting without actually  

1200
01:53:04,080 --> 01:53:07,120
attaining this kind of understanding, and 
that's the problem from your point of view. 

1201
01:53:07,120 --> 01:53:13,440
You want to change your job description so that 
you are internalizing these chunks and just  

1202
01:53:13,440 --> 01:53:18,000
getting this kind of integration each time.
It seems to me that what that means is you  

1203
01:53:18,000 --> 01:53:22,560
actually want to change the structure 
of the work output at some level. 

1204
01:53:27,360 --> 01:53:32,960
There’s this terrible idea that lots of people 
have that they should be in flow all of the time. 

1205
01:53:34,160 --> 01:53:37,680
And as far as I can tell, high performers 
just don't believe this at all. 

1206
01:53:38,240 --> 01:53:41,920
They're in flow some of the time.
You certainly see this with athletes. 

1207
01:53:41,920 --> 01:53:45,280
When they're actually out there 
playing basketball or tennis,  

1208
01:53:46,560 --> 01:53:51,200
ideally they are in flow much of the time.
But when they're training they're not. 

1209
01:53:51,200 --> 01:53:54,320
They're stuck a lot of the time, 
or they're doing things badly. 

1210
01:53:55,040 --> 01:54:00,400
I suppose I wonder what that looks like for you.
That I would be extremely satisfied with. 

1211
01:54:00,400 --> 01:54:06,880
The problem is I just don't know what 
the equivalent of doing 64 laps is. 

1212
01:54:06,880 --> 01:54:12,960
This is a thing you can change by choosing 
guests where there is a legible curriculum. 

1213
01:54:12,960 --> 01:54:18,720
So maybe it's a mistake not to have done that.
Also, there's no real way to prep for Terence Tao. 

1214
01:54:19,840 --> 01:54:25,920
There's no curriculum that's a plausible one.
There are many failure modes, but one  

1215
01:54:28,720 --> 01:54:34,320
long-term dynamic I'm worried about is that you 
can have a good podcast and reach a local maximum,  

1216
01:54:34,320 --> 01:54:38,720
but for no particular guest or 
topic are you going deep enough. 

1217
01:54:39,680 --> 01:54:44,880
My model of learning is that if you don't really 
understand the deeper mechanism, you're just  

1218
01:54:44,880 --> 01:54:49,280
mapping inputs and outputs of a black box.
That just fades incredibly fast or is  

1219
01:54:49,280 --> 01:54:53,200
