always a next question you can ask a chatbot. 

1278
02:00:17,280 --> 02:00:25,040
Yeah. And it's somewhat valuable. That’s part of 
the seductiveness, of course. It's not actually  

1279
02:00:25,040 --> 02:00:31,840
useless. But it can substitute for actually 
doing the thing that maybe you should be doing.  

1280
02:00:33,840 --> 02:00:41,360
It’s interesting. To what extent should 
you be outsourcing that kind of stuff?  

1281
02:00:43,680 --> 02:00:54,480
It’s an interesting judgment call. There is a 
whole bunch of routine work that you want done. 

1282
02:00:55,920 --> 02:01:01,040
It's low value for you, so if you can 
get a chatbot to do it, you may as well. 

1283
02:01:01,040 --> 02:01:04,640
Somebody interviewed the pioneering 
computer scientist Alan Kay years ago,  

1284
02:01:04,640 --> 02:01:09,760
and he was asked what he thought about Linux.
If I remember his answer correctly, he basically  

1285
02:01:09,760 --> 02:01:13,360
said, "It doesn't have anything 
to do with computer science. 

1286
02:01:13,360 --> 02:01:17,680
It's just a great big ball of mud.
There are a few interesting ideas  

1287
02:01:17,680 --> 02:01:24,240
in there which are worth understanding, but 
mostly all you're learning is stuff about Linux. 

1288
02:01:24,800 --> 02:01:27,440
You're not actually learning 
anything which is transferable." 

1289
02:01:27,440 --> 02:01:32,800
I thought that was very interesting.
There's a certain kind of seductiveness  

1290
02:01:33,760 --> 02:01:38,160
to some things where it's sort 
of a Rube Goldberg machine. 

1291
02:01:38,160 --> 02:01:42,080
You can just learn about all the 
bits, and it feels entertaining. 

1292
02:01:42,720 --> 02:01:47,280
But if you step back and think about 
what you're actually doing here,  

1293
02:01:48,400 --> 02:01:52,880
it might not actually be meeting your objectives.
Maybe you want to become a sysadmin, and learning  

1294
02:01:52,880 --> 02:01:57,360
Linux is a great use of your time.
There's no harm in that at all. 

1295
02:01:57,360 --> 02:02:03,840
But if your objective is to understand the 
fundamentals of computing, it's much less  

1296
02:02:03,840 --> 02:02:08,400
clear that that's a good use of your time.
It was certainly an answer I've thought a  

1297
02:02:08,400 --> 02:02:17,120
lot about, where for a certain type of mind, 
there is a seductiveness in just learning  

1298
02:02:17,120 --> 02:02:24,240
systems and confusing that with understanding.
Okay, I'll keep you updated on how this goes. 

1299
02:02:24,240 --> 02:02:28,800
I owe you a text within a month 
of some revamped learning system. 

1300
02:02:28,800 --> 02:02:33,120
I'd be really curious. It's also true 
that tiny incremental improvements  

1301
02:02:33,120 --> 02:02:39,360
in this are just worth so much.
It's the main input into the podcast. 

1302
02:02:39,920 --> 02:02:43,040
It's great that the bookshelves are fancy 
and I've got a blackboard or whatever,  

1303
02:02:43,040 --> 02:02:47,520
but really the thing that makes the podcast 
better is if I can improve the learning I do. 

1304
02:02:47,520 --> 02:02:58,400
So yes, it's worth every morsel of improvement.
All right, thanks for the therapy session. Great  

1305
02:02:58,400 --> 02:03:02,964
note to end on. Thanks, Michael.
All right. Thanks, Dwarkesh.

